# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vietnam
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] The **16th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 16 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, Asia, the Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean, Central America, the Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 13 hours, 5 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 11 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] After World War II, the parallel divided former French Indochina between Chinese administration in the north and British administrationin the south (see Allied post-war occupation of Vietnam).
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] In the Chadian–Libyan conflict, from 1984 the parallel, known as the "Red Line", delineated areas controlled by opposing combatants.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] Previously the Red Line had been the 15th parallel north.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] The **17th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 17 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] The parallel is particularly significant in the history of Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 13 hours, 9 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 7 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] The **Seventeenth parallel** (Vietnamese: *vĩ tuyến 17*) was the provisional military demarcation line between North and South Vietnam established by the Geneva Accords of 1954.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] The demarcation line did not exactly coincide with the 17th parallel but ran south of it, approximately along the Bến Hải River in Quảng Trị province to the village of Bo Ho Su and from there due west to the Laos–Vietnam border.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] In 1976 the demarcation line was made irrelevant as Vietnam was unified after the surrender of the South Vietnamese government.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] The **18th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 18 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 13 hours, 13 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 3 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] The **19th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 19 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, Asia, the Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean, North America, the Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 13 hours, 17 minutes during the summer solstice and 10 hours, 59 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] The **20th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 20 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] The parallel defines part of the border between Libya and Sudan.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] Within Sudan it defines the border between the Northern and North Darfur states.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 13 hours, 21 minutes during the summer solstice and 10 hours, 55 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] On 21 June, the maximum altitude of the sun is 93.44 degrees and 46.56 degrees on 21 December.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] In this case an angle larger than 90° means that the culmination takes place at a maximum altitude of 86.56 degrees in the opposite cardinal direction.
[src:vietnam/16th-parallel-north] In the northern torrid zone, the Sun remains in the south during winter, but can reach over the zenith to the north in midsummer.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The **Geneva Conference** was intended to settle outstanding issues resulting from the Korean War and the First Indochina War and involved several nations.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] It took place in Geneva, Switzerland, from 26 April to 21 July 1954.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The part of the conference on the Korean question ended without adopting any declarations or proposals and so is generally considered less relevant.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On the other hand, the Geneva Accords that dealt with the dismantling of French Indochina proved to have long-lasting repercussions.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Diplomats from South Korea, North Korea, China, the Soviet Union, and the United States dealt with the Korean side of the conference.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On the Indochina issue, the conference involved representatives from France, China, the Soviet Union, the United States, the United Kingdom, the Democratic Republic of Vietnam (DRV), the State of Vietnam, the Kingdom of Laos, and the Kingdom of Cambodia.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Three binding ceasefire agreements about Indochina ended hostilities in Vietnam, Laos, and Cambodia.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Pathet Lao were confined to two provinces in northern Laos, and Khmer Issarak forces disbanded.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Vietnam was partitioned at the 17th parallel, with troops and personnel of the DRV regrouping to the North, and those of the State of Vietnam regrouping to the South.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Alongside them, a non‑legally binding *Final Declaration* called for international supervision (via the International Control Commission), prohibited the introduction of foreign troops and bases in Vietnam, affirmed that the 17th parallel was only a provisional border.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Worsening relations between the North (communist) and the South (anti-communist) would eventually lead to the Vietnam War.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] As such, historians generally regard the Geneva Conference as failing to secure lasting peace in Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The conference was held at the Palace of Nations in Geneva, commencing on 26 April 1954.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The first agenda item was the Korean question to be followed by Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] "China's belligerent policies in Korea and Indochina", coupled with their increasing diplomatic closeness to the Soviet Union, would actively make China's international presence rather isolated.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Moreover, Zhou also stressed adopting a more "realistic" and moderate attitude which could deliver tangible results to the Indochina problem.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Following World War II, with the overthrow of French colonial rule and the surrender of Japan, the French returned to reconquer Indochina; meanwhile, the Vietnamese were locked in a civil strife over the destiny of their postcolonial state.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] After the communist-led Viet Minh purge of rival political parties and the breakdown of negotiations, tensions between the Viet Minh and Vietnamese non-communist authorities erupted into full-scale war in December 1946.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Initially weak, the Viet Minh pursued guerrilla warfare under the pretext of fighting against the French.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] In 1950, communist China and the Soviet Union recognized the Democratic Republic of Vietnam (DRV), while the United States and several other Western countries recognized the French-associated State of Vietnam (SVN).
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The colonial war and the civil war in Indochina became internationalized and intertwined with the global Cold War.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The US provided substantial aid to the SVN through France, while China and, to a lesser extent, the Soviet Union aided the DRV.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] After a series of offensives, hostilities culminated in a decisive French defeat at the Battle of Dien Bien Phu, resulting in the convening of the Geneva Conference.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] It was decided that Vietnam would be divided at the 17th parallel, at which time democratic elections would be held under international supervision and auspices.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] All parties agreed to the proposed partition of Vietnam, except the US and the SVN.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Viet Minh refused to hold free elections under United Nations supervision.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The South Korean representative proposed that the South Korean government was the only legal government in Korea, that UN-supervised elections should be held in the North, that Chinese forces should withdraw, and that UN forces, a belligerent party in the war, should remain as a police force.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Chinese delegation proposed an amendment to have a group of 'neutral' nations supervise the elections, which the North accepted.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The U.S. supported the South Korean position, saying that the USSR wanted to turn North Korea into a puppet state.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Most allies remained silent and at least one, Britain, thought that the South Korean–U.S. proposal would be deemed unreasonable.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The South Korean representative proposed that all-Korea elections, be held according to South Korean constitutional procedures and still under UN supervision.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On June 15, the last day of the conference on the Korean question, the USSR and China both submitted declarations in support of a unified, democratic, independent Korea, saying that negotiations to that end should resume at an appropriate time.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Belgian and British delegations said that while they were not going to accept "the Soviet and Chinese proposals, that did not mean a rejection of the ideas they contained".
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] In the end, however, the conference participants did not agree on any declaration.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] While the delegates had begun to assemble in Geneva in late April, the discussions on Indochina did not begin until 8 May 1954.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Viet Minh had achieved their decisive victory over the French Union forces at Dien Bien Phu the previous day.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Western allies did not have a unified position on what the Conference was to achieve in relation to Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Anthony Eden, leading the British delegation, favored a negotiated settlement to the conflict.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Georges Bidault, leading the French delegation, was keen to preserve something of France's position in Indochina to justify past sacrifices, even as the nation's military situation deteriorated.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The US had been supporting the French in Indochina for many years and the Republican Eisenhower administration wanted to ensure that it could not be accused of another "Yalta" or of having "lost" Indochina to the Communists.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Its leaders had previously accused the Democratic Truman administration of having "lost China" when the Communists were unexpectedly successful in securing control of virtually all of the country.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Eisenhower administration had considered air strikes in support of the French at Dien Bien Phu through the Operation Vulture but was unable to obtain a commitment to united action from key allies such as the United Kingdom.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Eisenhower was wary of becoming drawn into "another Korea" that would be deeply unpopular with the American public.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] US domestic policy considerations strongly influenced the country's position at Geneva.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Secretary of State John Foster Dulles, an anticommunist, forbade any contact with the Chinese delegation, refusing to shake hands with Zhou Enlai, the lead Chinese negotiator.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Dulles fell out with the UK delegate Anthony Eden over the perceived failure of the UK to support united action and US positions on Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] He left Geneva on 3 May and was replaced by his deputy, Walter Bedell Smith.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The State of Vietnam refused to attend the negotiations until Bidault wrote to Bảo Đại, assuring him that any agreement would not partition Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Bidault opened the conference on 8 May by proposing a cessation of hostilities, a ceasefire in place, a release of prisoners of war, and a disarming of irregulars, despite the French surrender at Dien Bien Phu the previous day in northwestern Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Pham Van Dong first proposed a partition of Vietnam on 25 May.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Following their victory at Dien Bien Phu and given the worsening French security position around the Red River Delta, a ceasefire and partition would not appear to have been in the interests of the DRV.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] It appears that the DRV leadership thought the balance of forces was uncomfortably close and was worried about morale problems in the troops and supporters, after eight years of war.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Turner has argued that the Viet Minh might have prolonged the negotiations and continued fighting to achieve a more favorable position militarily, if not for Chinese and Soviet pressure on them to end the fighting.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] In addition, there was a widespread perception that the Diem government would collapse, leaving the Viet Minh free to take control of the area.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On 12 May, the State of Vietnam rejected any partition of the country, and the U.S. expressed a similar position the next day.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The French sought to implement a physical separation of the opposing forces into enclaves throughout the country, known as the "leopard-skin" approach.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The DRV/Viet Minh would be given the Cà Mau Peninsula, three enclaves near Saigon, large areas of Annam and Tonkin; the French Union forces would retain most urban areas and the Red River Delta, including Hanoi and Haiphong, allowing it to resume combat operation in the north, if necessary.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Behind the scenes, the U.S. and the French governments continued to discuss the terms for possible U.S. military intervention in Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] By 29 May, the U.S. and the French had reached an agreement that if the Conference failed to deliver an acceptable peace deal, Eisenhower would seek Congressional approval for military intervention in Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] However, after discussions with the Australian and New Zealand governments in which it became evident that neither would support U.S. military intervention, reports of the plummeting morale among the French Union forces and opposition from U.S.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Army Chief of Staff Matthew Ridgway, the U.S. began to shift away from intervention and continued to oppose a negotiated settlement.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] By early to mid-June, the U.S. began to consider the possibility that rather than supporting the French in Indochina, it might be preferable for the French to leave and for the U.S. to support the new Indochinese states.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] That would remove the taint of French colonialism.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Unwilling to support the proposed partition or intervention, by mid-June, the U.S. decided to withdraw from major participation in the Conference.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On 15 June, Vyacheslav Molotov proposed that the ceasefire should be monitored by a supervisory commission, chaired by non-aligned India.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On 16 June, Zhou Enlai stated that the situations in Vietnam, Cambodia, and Laos were not the same and should be treated separately.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] He proposed that Laos and Cambodia could be treated as neutral nations if they had no foreign bases.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On 18 June, Pham Van Dong said the Viet Minh would be prepared to withdraw their forces from Laos and Cambodia if no foreign bases were established in Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The apparent softening of the Communist position appeared to arise from a meeting among the DRV, Chinese and Soviet delegations on 15 June in which Zhou warned the Viet Minh that its military presence in Laos and Cambodia threatened to undermine negotiations in relation to Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] That represented a major blow to the DRV, which had tried to ensure that the Pathet Lao and Khmer Issarak would join the governments in Laos and Cambodia, respectively, under the leadership of the DRV.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Chinese likely also sought to ensure that Laos and Cambodia were not under Vietnam's influence in the future but under China's.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On 18 June, following a vote of no-confidence, the French Laniel government fell and was replaced by a coalition with Radical Pierre Mendès France as Prime Minister, by a vote of 419 to 47, with 143 abstentions.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Prior to the collapse of the Laniel government, France recognized the State of Vietnam as "a fully independent and sovereign state" on 4 June.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] A long-time opponent of the war, Mendès France had pledged to the National Assembly that he would resign if he failed to achieve a ceasefire within 30 days.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Mendès France retained the Foreign Ministry for himself, and Bidault left the Conference.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The new French government abandoned earlier assurances to the State of Vietnam that France would not pursue or accept partition, and it engaged in secret negotiations with the Viet Minh delegation, bypassing the State of Vietnam to meet Mendès France's self-imposed deadline.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On 23 June, Mendès France secretly met with Zhou Enlai at the French embassy in Bern.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Zhou outlined the Chinese position that an immediate ceasefire was required, the three nations should be treated separately, and the two governments that existed in Vietnam would be recognized.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The following day he met with his main advisers on Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] General Paul Ély outlined the deteriorating military position in Vietnam, and Jean Chauvel suggested that the situation on the ground called for partition at the 16th or 17th parallel.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The three agreed that the Bao Dai government would need time to consolidate its position and that U.S. assistance would be vital.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The possibility of retaining Hanoi and Haiphong or just Haiphong was dismissed, as the French believed it was preferable to seek partition with no Viet Minh enclaves in the south.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On 16 June, twelve days after France granted full independence to the State of Vietnam, Bao Dai appointed Ngo Dinh Diem as Prime Minister to replace Bửu Lộc.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Diem was a staunch nationalist, both anti-French and anticommunist.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Diem agreed to take the position if he received all civilian and military powers.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Diem and his foreign minister, Tran Van Do, were strongly opposed to partition.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Also on 28 June, Tạ Quang Bửu, a senior DRV negotiator, called for the line of partition to be at the 13th parallel, the withdrawal of all French Union forces from the north within three months of the ceasefire, and the Pathet Lao to have virtual sovereignty over eastern Laos.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] From 3 to 5 July, Zhou Enlai met with Ho Chi Minh and other senior DRV leaders in Liuzhou, Guangxi.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Wei Guoqing, the chief Chinese military adviser to the Viet Minh, said he agreed.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] "If the U.S. does not interfere,' Zhou asked, "and assuming France will dispatch more troops, how long will it take for us to seize the whole of Indochina?" In the best scenario, Giap replied, "full victory could be achieved in two to three years.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] That afternoon Zhou "offered a lengthy exposition on the massive international reach of the Indochina conflict ... and on the imperative of preventing an American intervention in the war.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The central issue", Zhou told Ho, is "to prevent America's intervention" and "to achieve a peaceful settlement." Laos and Cambodia would have to be treated differently and be allowed to pursue their own paths if they did not join a military alliance or permit foreign bases on their territory.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Several days later the Communist Party of Vietnam's Sixth Central Committee plenum took place.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Ho Chi Minh and General Secretary Trường Chinh took turns emphasizing the need for an early political settlement to prevent military intervention by the United States, now the "main and direct enemy" of Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] "In the new situation we cannot follow the old program," Ho declared.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] A demarcation line allowing the temporary regrouping of both sides would be necessary ..." The plenum endorsed Ho's analysis, passing a resolution supporting a compromise settlement to end the fighting.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] However, Ho and Truong Chinh plainly worried that following such an agreement in Geneva, there would be internal discontent and "leftist deviation", and in particular, analysts would fail to see the complexity of the situation and underestimate the power of the American and French adversaries.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] They accordingly reminded their colleagues that France would retain control of a large part of the country and that people living in the area might be confused, alienated, and vulnerable to enemy manipulations.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Conference reconvened on 10 July, and Mendès France arrived to lead the French delegation.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The State of Vietnam continued to protest against partition which had become inevitable, with the only issue being where the line should be drawn.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Walter Bedell Smith from the U.S. arrived in Geneva on 16 July, but the U.S. delegation was under instructions to avoid direct association with the negotiations.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] All parties at the Conference called for reunification elections but could not agree on the details.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Pham Van Dong proposed elections under the supervision of "local commissions." The U.S., with the support of Britain and the Associated States of Vietnam, Laos, and Cambodia, suggested UN supervision.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] That was rejected by Molotov, who argued for a commission with an equal number of communist and noncommunist members, which could determine "important" issues only by unanimous agreement.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The negotiators were unable to agree on a date for the elections for reunification.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The DRV argued that the elections should be held within six months of the ceasefire, and the Western allies sought to have no deadline.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Molotov proposed June 1955 then softened to later in 1955 and finally July 1956.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Diem government supported reunification elections but only with effective international supervision; it argued that genuinely free elections were impossible in the totalitarian North.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] By the afternoon of 20 July, the remaining outstanding issues were resolved as the parties agreed that the partition line should be at the 17th parallel and that the elections for reunification should be in July 1956, two years after the ceasefire.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The "Agreement on the Cessation of Hostilities in Vietnam" was signed only by French and Viet Minh military commands.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Based on a proposal by Zhou Enlai, an International Control Commission (ICC) chaired by India, with Canada and Poland as members, was placed in charge of supervising the ceasefire.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Because issues were to be decided unanimously, Poland's presence in the ICC provided the communists' effective veto power over supervision of the treaty.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The unsigned "Final Declaration of the Geneva Conference" called for reunification elections, which the majority of delegates expected to be supervised by the ICC.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] While the three agreements (later known as the Geneva Accords) were dated 20 July (to meet Mendès France's 30-day deadline) they were in fact signed on the morning of 21 July.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The agreement was signed by the Democratic Republic of Vietnam, France, the People's Republic of China, the Soviet Union, and the United Kingdom.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The State of Vietnam rejected the agreement, while the United States stated that it "took note" of the ceasefire agreements and declared that it would "refrain from the threat or use of force to disturb them.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Division at the 17th Parallel meant that the Democratic Republic of Vietnam was giving up a large area currently under its control south of that line while gaining only a very small area, not already under its control, north of the line.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Separate accords were signed by the signatories with the Kingdom of Cambodia and the Kingdom of Laos in relation to Cambodia and Laos respectively.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Following the terms of the agreement, Laos would be governed by the Royal Lao Government, while Cambodia would be ruled by the royal court of Norodom Sihanouk.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Despite retaining its monarchy, the agreement also allowed for "VWP-affiliated Laotian forces" to run the provinces of Xam Neua and Phongsaly, further expanding North Vietnamese influence within Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Communist forces in Cambodia, however, would remain out of power.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The British and Communist Chinese delegations reached an agreement on the sidelines of the Conference to upgrade their diplomatic relations.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The DRV at Geneva accepted a much worse settlement than the military situation on the ground indicated.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] "For Ho Chi Minh, there was no getting around the fact that his victory, however unprecedented and stunning was incomplete and perhaps temporary.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The vision that had always driven him on, that of a 'great union' of all Vietnamese, had flickered into view for a fleeting moment in 1945–46, then had been lost in the subsequent war.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] France had achieved a much better outcome than could have been expected.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] In a press conference on 21 July, US President Eisenhower expressed satisfaction that a ceasefire had been concluded but stated that the US was not a party to the Accords or bound by them, as they contained provisions that his administration could not support.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Both the State of Vietnam and the United States of America rejected the partition of Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On 9 October 1954, the tricolore was lowered for the last time at the Hanoi Citadel and the last French Union forces left the city, crossing the Paul Doumer Bridge on their way to Haiphong for embarkation.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] A military demarcation line shall be fixed, on either side of which the forces of the two parties shall be regrouped after their withdrawal, the Communist North Vietnam to the north of the line and the forces of the Free World South Vietnam to the south.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] After the cessation of hostilities, a large migration took place.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] North Vietnamese, especially Catholics, intellectuals, business people, land owners, anti-communist democrats, and members of the middle class moved south of the Accords-mandated ceasefire line during Operation Passage to Freedom.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The ICC reported that at least 892,876 North Vietnamese were processed through official refugee stations.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The CIA attempted to further influence Catholic Vietnamese with slogans such as "the Virgin Mary is moving South".
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The CIA's role in influencing the immigrants' decisions was minimal, since Catholic migrants were motivated mainly by their own convictions and circumstances rather than by external propaganda.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] At least 500,000 Catholics, approximately 200,000 Buddhists, and tens of thousands from ethnic minority groups migrated to the South.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] More might have left, but according to the Canadian members of the international peacekeeping mission, many North Vietnamese were prevented from leaving by "soldiers, political cadres, and local militias".
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Around the same time, between 14,000 – 45,000 civilians and approximately 100,000 Viet Minh fighters moved in the opposite direction.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The U.S. replaced the French as a political backup for Ngo Dinh Diem, the Prime Minister of the State of Vietnam, who asserted his power in the South.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Geneva conference had not provided any specific mechanisms for the national elections planned for 1956, and Diem refused to hold them by citing that the South had not signed and was not bound to the Geneva Accords and that it was impossible to hold free elections in the communist North.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] On 20 May 1955, French Union forces withdrew from Saigon to a coastal base and on 28 April 1956, the last French forces left Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] In July 1955, the prime minister of the State of Vietnam, Ngô Đình Diệm, announced that South Vietnam would not participate in elections to unify the country.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] He said that the State of Vietnam had not signed the Geneva Accords and was therefore not bound by it.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The failure of reunification led to the creation of the National Liberation Front (better known as the Viet Cong) by Ho Chi Minh's government.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] They were closely aided by the Vietnam People's Army (VPA) of the North, also known as the North Vietnamese Army.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] The Vietnamese communist leadership never expected the 1956 election to take place, nor did they believe peaceful reunification was possible.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] They saw military force as the only way to reunite the country but continued to raise the election issue for its propaganda value.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Despite glaring errors with the partition, the Chinese would still manage to largely benefit from the conference's results.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] In addition to gaining an independent North Vietnam, China would also open up "dialogues with France, Britain, and the United States".
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Furthermore, China, as a result of this expanded and moderate international approach, also helped to weaken America's attempt to label China as a "Red" radical within the region.
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Historian John Lewis Gaddis said that the 1954 accords "were so hastily drafted and ambiguously worded that, from the standpoint of international law, it makes little sense to speak of violations from either side".
[src:vietnam/1954-geneva-conference] Historian Christopher Goscha pointed out that while the Geneva Conference brought an end to French fighting, it failed to prevent the resurgence of a Vietnamese civil war or more direct American military involvement in Indochina.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] A referendum was held in the State of Vietnam (South Vietnam) to determine whether the country was a republic or monarchy.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] It was primarily a contest between Prime Minister Ngô Đình Diệm, who proposed a republic, and former emperor Bảo Đại, who had abdicated in 1945 and at the time of the referendum held the title of head of state.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The referendum was the last phase in the power struggle between Bảo Đại and his prime minister.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Bảo Đại disliked Diệm and had frequently attempted to undermine him, having appointed him only because he was a conduit to American aid.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] At the time, the country was going through a period of insecurity, as Vietnam had been temporarily partitioned as a result of the 1954 Geneva Accords that ended the First Indochina War.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The State of Vietnam controlled the southern half of the country, pending national elections that were intended to reunify the country under a common government.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Still, the Vietnamese National Army was not in full control of southern Vietnam; the Cao Đài and Hòa Hảo religious sects ran their own administrations in the countryside supported by private armies, while the Bình Xuyên organised crime syndicate controlled the streets of Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Despite interference from these groups, Bảo Đại, and even French officials, Diệm managed to subdue the private armies and consolidate government control over the country by mid-1955.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Emboldened by his success, Diệm began to plot Bảo Đại's downfall.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] He scheduled a referendum for 23 October 1955 and pushed Bảo Đại out of the political scene, hindering the former emperor's attempts to derail the poll.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In the period leading up to the vote, campaigning for Bảo Đại was banned, while Diệm's election campaign focused on personal attacks against Bảo Đại.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] These included pornographic cartoons of the head of state and unverified rumours claiming he was illegitimate and linking him to various mistresses.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The government-controlled media launched polemical attacks on Bảo Đại, and police went door-to-door, warning people of the consequences of failing to vote.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] After his brother Ngô Đình Nhu had rigged the referendum, Diệm proclaimed himself president of the newly created Republic of Vietnam on 26 October 1955.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] A year later, the republic promulgated a constitution and established its own parliament.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The defeat of the French Army at Điện Biên Phủ in 1954, followed by the Geneva Accords, led to a divided Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The French-backed State of Vietnam, led by former Emperor Bảo Đại, provisionally held control south of the 17th parallel.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Hồ Chí Minh's Viet Minh held the north under the Democratic Republic of Vietnam, which Hồ Chí Minh had proclaimed in 1945.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The agreements stated that nationwide elections were to be held in 1956 to unify the country under a common government.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In July 1954, during the transition period, Bảo Đại appointed Diệm as Prime Minister of the State of Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] However the State of Vietnam as an independent government did not sign the agreement.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On 11 October 1954, the border was closed by the International Control Commission, after a period of 300 days during which free passage between both halves of Vietnam had been allowed.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Under the Geneva Accords, anti-communist military personnel were obliged to evacuate to the south, while communist forces were to be moved north.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Civilians were free to move to whichever zone they preferred.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The issue was a topic of concern for either side throughout the course of the 300 days: Operation Freedom Passage followed with transportation options for civilians to move to the south, and Diệm authorizing U.S.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] CIA adviser Colonel Edward Lansdale to stage campaign intended to convince more people to move to South Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In the end, between 800,000 and 1,000,000 people migrated to the south, many of them Catholics.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] At the start of 1955, French Indochina was dissolved, leaving Diệm in temporary control of the south.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] At the time, Diệm had little authority beyond the gates of his own palace.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Bảo Đại had little confidence in him and gave him meagre support—the pair had clashed in the past, with Diệm resigning as Bảo Đại's Interior Minister two decades earlier, believing the head of state to be weak and ineffective.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Many historians believe that Bảo Đại may have selected Diệm for the latter's ability to attract U.S. support and funding.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] During the transition period, the French Expeditionary Corps maintained a presence in South Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] This led to tension between France and the State of Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm, a passionate nationalist, detested the French, who reciprocated, hoping he would fail, even calling for his removal on occasions.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm faced challenges to his authority from four more groups.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The Hòa Hảo and Cao Đài religious sects had private armies that controlled the Mekong Delta and the areas west of Saigon, respectively.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The Bình Xuyên was an armed, organised crime empire that controlled much of Saigon with a 40,000 strong private army, while the Vietminh still controlled much of the rural area.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm's Vietnamese National Army (VNA) was led by General Nguyễn Văn Hinh, a French citizen who loathed and frequently disobeyed him.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Bảo Đại sold the operating license of the national police to the Bình Xuyên, effectively putting administrative control of the police in the hands of a crime syndicate.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Amid growing French and US skepticism of his ability to provide stable rule, Diệm forced the matter to a head in April 1955.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] He ordered the Bình Xuyên to relinquish control of the National Police and submit to his command by integrating into the VNA or disbanding, threatening to crush them if they refused.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] He bribed Hòa Hảo and Cao Đài commanders into joining the VNA, gradually resulting in the defection of some commanders and their units, while others continued to lead their forces against Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On 27 April, the VNA initiated the Battle for Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] After a brief but violent battle that left between 500 and 1,000 people dead and about 20,000 homeless, the Bình Xuyên were crushed.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm had regained both U.S. confidence and control of the police.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Jubilant crowds lauded Diệm and denounced Bảo Đại, who had tried to dismiss him in the middle of the battle to prevent him from quelling the Bình Xuyên.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In addition, General Paul Ely, the head of the French presence in Vietnam, tried to impede Diệm; his troops put road blocks against the VNA and gave intelligence to the Bình Xuyên.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Buoyed by his successes, and fueled by increased hatred of both the French and Bảo Đại after their attempts to prevent him from dismantling the Bình Xuyên, Diệm became more confident as he went about consolidating his hold on power.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On 15 May, Diệm abolished Bảo Đại's Imperial Guard; its 5,000 men became the 11th and 42nd Infantry Regiments of the VNA.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm then stripped Bảo Đại of his extensive crown lands.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On 15 June, Diệm had the Council of the Royal Family at Huế declare that Bảo Đại be stripped of his powers, and that he, Diệm, be made president.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Bảo Đại's relatives condemned him for abdicating as head of state, and for his links with France and the Bình Xuyên.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Historians have speculated that the royals agreed to turn on Bảo Đại so Diệm would not seize their assets.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On 7 July 1955, the first anniversary of his installation as prime minister, Diệm announced that a national referendum would be held to determine the future of the country.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm contended that the Communists would never allow free elections in the north, so therefore South Vietnam must strike out on its own and establish a separate, non-Communist state.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] This was echoed by the Saigon press, which ran articles assailing communist elections as shambolic, rigged, and meaningless; at the time, the northern half of Vietnam had a greater population than the south.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] A month earlier, North Vietnamese Prime Minister Phạm Văn Đồng wrote to Saigon asking to begin negotiations over the specific details of the elections.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] While the Americans were happy to avoid elections because of fears of a communist victory, they hoped that Diệm would enter the dialogue over planning matters and wait for North Vietnam to object to a proposal, and thus use it to blame the communists for violating the Geneva Accords.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The Americans had earlier advised Diệm, who had been acting in defiance of Bảo Đại, that continued aid was contingent on Diệm establishing a legal basis for usurping the head of state's power.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On 6 October 1955, Diệm announced the referendum would be held on 23 October.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The election was open to men and women aged 18 or over, and the government arranged to have a polling station set up for every 1,000 registered voters.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The poll was contested by Bảo Đại, who had spent much of his time in France and advocated a monarchy, and Diệm, who ran on a republican platform.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] According to historian Jessica Chapman, it was a choice between "the country's obsolete emperor and its far-from-popular prime minister, Ngô Đình Diệm".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In announcing the referendum, Diệm portrayed his decision as being motivated by a love of democracy and popular discontent with the rule of Bảo Đại.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The prime minister cited a plethora of petitions from various social, religious, and political groups calling on him to stage a plebiscite to remove Bảo Đại, claiming he was motivated by these "legitimate and democratic" sentiments.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] U.S. officials advised Diệm to claim 60% and 70% of the vote to make the election look plausible.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Under the Elysee Accords and the subsequent legislation that created the State of Vietnam in 1949, Bảo Đại's position as head of state was neither permanent nor indefinite.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Sovereignty was presumed to rest solely upon the people, with Bảo Đại being a mere conduit.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] As a result, the referendum itself was within the law.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm had not been elected to his post, so he saw the referendum as an opportunity to rebuff opponents, who claimed that he was undemocratic and autocratic.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The event also gave Diệm an opportunity to boost his prestige by defeating Bảo Đại in a head-to-head contest.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] It was previously agreed that a National Assembly would be elected first, but Diệm went ahead with the plebiscite, which meant that he would have total power if he deposed Bảo Đại before a legislature was formed.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] U.S. diplomats were concerned that the move would be seen as a power grab, as Diệm was organising and driving an electoral process in which he was a candidate.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The Americans felt that a legislature should be formed first and that the body should oversee the referendum, but Diệm ignored their advice.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Frederick Reinhardt informed Washington that Diệm had no intention of allowing a level playing field for the opposition, and that the foreign press had already made much of Diệm's democratic pronouncements being a facade.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The Department of State agreed and opted to avoid trumpeting the referendum as an exercise in democracy for fear of attracting negative reactions to their foreign policy.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Nevertheless, U.S. officials in Vietnam were pleased with the referendum, as they saw it as an opportunity to strengthen South Vietnam and avoid defeat to the communists, as they saw a republican model as being more robust.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Having declared his disdain for the 1956 reunification elections, Diệm saw the referendum as the first step in creating a long-term state to rule over South Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] He repeatedly said that the creation of a legislature and a constitution for his new state would follow the referendum.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm reportedly saw the poll as an opportunity to legitimise him as a symbol of Vietnamese democracy, so that he could frame and justify his refusal to participate in national elections as a struggle between freedom and communist authoritarianism.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm asserted that South Vietnam would eventually reunify the nation under a democratic administration and liberate their northern compatriots from communist oppression, and championed the referendum as a first step in nurturing democracy.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] His support base was to use this as a means of justifying the deposal of Bảo Đại, citing past decisions that according to them, were pro-communist.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm ran a personal attack campaign against the head of state, for whom campaigning was prohibited.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The army and national police went about enforcing the ban on pro-Bảo Đại and anti-Diệm activities.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Police went from door to door, explaining the consequences of failing to vote.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] They organized conferences in rural villages and addressed the populace with loudspeakers.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In general, Diệm's line of attack was to portray Bảo Đại as a drunken womanizer who was preoccupied with immoral pleasures and unconcerned with the problems of the populace.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Vietnam's monarchic tradition was built on Confucianism and the emperor's Mandate of Heaven, and Diệm's campaign claimed Bảo Đại had lost this mandate through his debauched lifestyle.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] According to Joseph Buttinger, who was based in Vietnam as the second in command at the International Rescue Committee, the methods used to influence the poll were "outrageous".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Donald Lancaster, a journalist who covered the poll, said "Whereas Bảo Đại was given no opportunity to defend himself, the government-controlled press proceeded to overwhelm him with scurrilous abuse." Diệm later banned Bảo Đại from entering the State of Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm's advertising included the parading of giant pageant-style floats of Bảo Đại through the streets of Saigon, depicted with bags of money on his shoulders, a deck of cards in his hands, and with naked blonde women and a bottle of cognac in his arms.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] This was a reference to the head of state's reputation for opulence, gambling and womanising.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In particular, the blonde hair referred to Bảo Đại's purported penchant for European mistresses with whom he liaised on the French Riviera.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Bảo Đại's dummy was accompanied by that of a Frenchman putting gold into his pockets, thereby questioning his nationalist credentials.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Posters and effigies with Bảo Đại having a pig's head were disseminated, while a prominent newspaper composed and encouraged the people to sing songs insulting Bảo Đại.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Walls and public transport were plastered with slogans, including "Beware of the evil king Bảo Đại's preference for gambling, women, wine, milk, and butter.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Whoever votes for him is a traitor." Aside from referring to his opulent lifestyle, other slogans such as "Bảo Đại, the traitorous puppet king", and "Bảo Đại, warden of gambling dens and brothels", referred to his alleged softness towards the communists.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The radio was used to verbally abuse Bảo Đại, accusing him of treason and corruption.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On the other hand, Diệm was described as a "hero of the people" and "father of the nation".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm's government-controlled press overwhelmed Bảo Đại with endless personal propaganda attacks, with special editions of newspapers being devoted to polemical biographical accounts of the former emperor.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] This allowed Diệm's campaign to condemn Bảo Đại with much more salacious detail than was possible through mere slogans.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] This started in August when the daily newspaper *Thoi Dai* started a three-week series that disseminated unsubstantiated and scandalous details about Bảo Đại's life.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] These were written by editorialist Hong Van, who called Bảo Đại a "cockroach who sold his country for personal glory".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Van claimed Bảo Đại was the illegitimate son of Emperor Khải Định, alleging Khải Định had been infertile and married a maid, before claiming the maid's son, by another man, as his own.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The paper claimed Bảo Đại was "big yet foolish, had many children, and was very fond of women" while Khải Định was uncomfortable with females, hinting that the different personalities were inconsistent with a common biological lineage.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Capitalising on anti-French sentiment, the paper went on to discuss Bảo Đại's upbringing in France, claiming that he was already womanising as a teenager because of his European upbringing.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Bảo Đại later married an ethnic Vietnamese French citizen, who became Empress Nam Phương, who had been raised Catholic.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The editorials accused her of being a French agent and claimed she had treated the queen mother badly, a serious character flaw as Confucianism strongly emphasized respect for elders.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Hong Van went on to claim that Bảo Đại's sequence of Gallic lovers was an indication that colonial officials were successfully using sex to turn the head of state into a puppet of France.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The culmination of the newspaper campaign was a satirical pornographic cartoon, entitled "The Story of Bảo Đại".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] It summarized the scandalous depictions of the head of state made by *Thoi Dai* in the preceding weeks and was published on 19 October, four days before the referendum.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The pictures featured full frontal nude depictions of Bảo Đại and his mistresses, their genitalia prominently exposed, including a frame showing a naked blonde performing an erotic dance for the head of state.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Aside from painting Bảo Đại as a sexually insatiable glutton, Diệm's campaign also attacked the head of state's nationalist credentials.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] They criticised him as being too soft in his dealings with French colonial authorities, and for serving as the head of state of the Empire of Vietnam, a puppet regime set up by Imperial Japan after they invaded during World War II.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] They also accused him of ceding half the country to the communists.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The communists had already captured more than half the country on the battlefield, and Bảo Đại claimed he had no choice, but Diệm's campaign portrayed him as incompetent and unwilling to take the blame.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm used the Ministry of Information's electoral education campaign as a partisan political tool.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Instead of using it purely to explain the democratic process, the campaign was used to extol Diệm and his allies.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On 15 October, Bảo Đại issued a statement protesting against the referendum.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] He urged the governments of France, the United Kingdom, the United States, India and even the Soviet Union not to recognise Diệm, asserting that he was an obstacle to the reunification of Vietnam under the Geneva Accords.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] He accused Diệm's poll of being "a governmental activity which conforms neither to the profound sentiment of the Vietnamese people nor to the common cause of peace".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On 18 October, he made the token gesture of formally dismissing Diệm.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The following day, he denounced "the police methods" of Diệm's "dictatorship" and warned the Vietnamese populace "against a regime that was bound to lead them to ruin, famine, and war".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Bảo Đại accused Diệm of trying to foment conflict between the French and the Americans.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] On the eve of the poll, Bảo Đại stated "I can even tell you that I know the percentage of favourable votes that Mr.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The staging of the election was subsidised by foreign funding.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The United States government and a combination of American Roman Catholic charities contributed US$2 million each.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Ba Cụt, a leader of an anti-government Hòa Hảo religious sect, distributed a pamphlet condemning Diệm as an American puppet, citing the funding as proof and further asserting that Diệm was going to "Catholicize" the country.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The Vietnamese Socialist Party, which was affiliated to the Hòa Hảo, claimed Diệm had "bribed the world of laborers and young students to petition in support of Diệm's rise to chief-of-state and to petition in favor of deposing Bao Dai", using the American election funding.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Another Hòa Hảo rebel leader, General Trần Văn Soái, assailed Diệm's undemocratic regime and declared the referendum illegal.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] He invited "friendly countries and the people of Vietnam to distrust this political maneuver".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm had earlier told a cabinet minister that there was only one political party and went about eradicating opposition by force.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Opponents claimed Diệm's declarations about the value of democracy were hollow.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Lansdale advised Diệm to print his ballots in red, while those of Bảo Đại were printed in green.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In Vietnam, red is associated with good luck and prosperity, whereas green is often associated with a cuckold and bad luck.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm's red ballots pictured him with youthful and modern-looking people, while Bảo Đại was placed in the old-fashioned robes he never wore.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In addition, Bảo Đại's portrait showed him to appear dazed and bloated, while Diệm and those surrounding him were smiling and appeared to be energetic.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The logistics of the referendum were organised and supervised by Diệm's brother and confidant, Ngô Đình Nhu, who was the leader of the family's secret Personalist Labor Revolutionary Party, which supplied the Ngôs' electoral base.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Reports of violence and intimidation were widespread.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] During the referendum, Nhu's staff told voters to throw away the green ballots.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Those who disobeyed were often chased down and beaten, with pepper sauce and water sometimes being forced into their nostrils.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The violations were particularly flagrant in central Vietnam, a region over which another of Diệm's younger brothers, Ngô Đình Cẩn, ruled.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Cẩn was based in the former imperial capital city of Huế, home of the Nguyễn dynasty and a source of support for Bảo Đại.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] He stifled this support by ordering the police to arrest 1,200 people for political reasons in the week leading up to the vote.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In the city of Hội An, several people were killed in election violence on the day of the poll.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Voting started at 07:00 and ended at 17:00.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm's government formulated procedural regulations ostensibly designed to ensure results and ballots were correctly accounted for and to prevent election fraud.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In reality however, the votes were counted without independent supervision, which resulted in Diệm being credited with 98.9% of the vote.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The prime minister tallied 605,025 votes in Saigon, although only 450,000 voters were registered in the capital.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm's tally also exceeded the registration numbers in other districts.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] French newspapers claimed that only half of the registered voters in Saigon had actually voted, and that the rest had boycotted the election, implying that more than 60% of the votes in the capital were not authentic.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Defenders of Diệm claim this was due to recently arrived, mostly Catholic, refugees from North Vietnam who voted without being enrolled, rather than large-scale ballot stuffing.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm's regime had announced that 5,335,668 people were eligible to vote, but when the results were declared, there were 5,784,752 ballots.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm's government claimed his candidacy had been endorsed by the mother of Bảo Đại, although Diệm had ordered the military to confiscate her family's property and evict her from the land.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The near unanimous voter turnout and support for Diệm was replicated in Central Highlands and Mekong Delta swamp areas, which were not even under the control of the government and its Vietnamese National Army.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In some districts of the Mekong Delta, overwhelming tallies for Diệm in excess of 90% of the registered voters were recorded, even though the Hòa Hảo warlord Ba Cụt and his army had prevented voting.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The referendum was widely condemned for being fraudulent.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] A CIA report written in 1966 adjudged the poll to be the most heavily manipulated in the first 11 years of South Vietnam's history.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The U.S. government privately concluded that the monopoly Diệm had on the media and the election campaign was a greater factor in the victory than intimidation and the fact that the voting was effectively public.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Reinhardt cabled Washington, saying that the "referendum proved [a] resounding success for [the] Diệm government".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] He indicated that the poll results were not necessarily a reflection of reality by adding that the result did not show that Diệm had majority support but that he was able to control the country, effectively unchallenged.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The U.S. government was heartened by Diệm's apparent ability to negate communist and other opposition.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Fall stated that "there is not the slightest doubt that this plebiscite was only a shade more fraudulent than most electoral tests under a dictatorship".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The American journalist Stanley Karnow cited the dubious plebiscite as evidence of Diệm's "mandarin mentality".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Chapman wrote that "... no amount of unilateral campaigning, anti-Bảo Đại sentiment, or Confucian political restraint could explain Diệm's 98 percent margin of victory in a politically heterogeneous South Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Corruption and intimidation must have played a significant role." Buttinger said that while the monarchy was "another rotten relic of Vietnam's past" and Bảo Đại "its last, unworthy representative", fraud and intimidation were unnecessary as Diệm would have won easily in any event.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Historian David Anderson said the victory "was not a true representation of Diệm's power or popularity.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The emperor's weakness, the disarray of the political opposition, and other such factors explain his triumph".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Three days after the vote, Diệm proclaimed the creation of the Republic of Vietnam, naming himself as its president.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Having claimed the election was entirely without irregularities, the United States government hailed Diệm as a new hero of the "free world".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Archives of policy discussions show that the Americans were concerned more about the negative image created by Diệm's autocratic and antidemocratic style among the international community, rather than its possible effects on national cohesion.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The US State Department spokesman said "the people of Viet-Nam have spoken, and we, of course, recognise their decision".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Reaction to Diệm's victory among the American press varied with geographic location.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Newspapers in the Midwest hailed Diệm's win as a triumph for democracy and extolled the new president as a champion of democracy.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] *Reader's Digest* called it an "overwhelming endorsement" and dubbed Diệm a "beacon of light, showing the way to free people".
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm's victory was seen as a blow to French stature in Vietnam, as the former colonial power had helped to set up Bảo Đại's State of Vietnam in 1949.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] They consistently opposed Diệm and his policies, and unsuccessfully tried to impede him.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The U.S. media regarded Diệm's victory as a signal that the United States would be the only Western power in South Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Some felt that this would enable Diệm to rule effectively without French hindrance, while others felt that this would leave too much of a burden on the American government.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The French media and diplomatic corps viewed the result as a humiliation.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Before the poll, French officials had privately predicted Diệm would dissolve the French High Command and use any victory as justification for scrapping the national reunification elections.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] The French media viewed the poll as undemocratic and a plot by the Americans to sabotage any prospect of national reunification, but France recognised the Republic of Vietnam soon after.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Diệm severed economic relations with France on 9 December 1955, and withdrew from the French Union shortly afterwards.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Neither the Soviet Union nor the People's Republic of China overtly objected to Diệm's actions in creating a new state in the southern half of Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] Nevertheless, by the time of Diệm's deposal and assassination in 1963, France bought 46.3% of South Vietnam's exports and accounted for most of the foreign investment in the country.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] French cultural influences and the language remained prevalent.
[src:vietnam/1955-state-of-vietnam-referendum] In January 1956, with no legislature and constitution in place, Diệm used his absolute power to dissolve the Revolutionary Council by launching police raids on the members, forcing those from the Cao Đài and Hòa Hảo who had rallied to his side to go on the run.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] During South Vietnam's later years, some referred to the coup as *Cách mạng 1-11-1963* (The 1st November 1963 Revolution).
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The Kennedy administration had been aware of the coup planning, but Cable 243 from the United States Department of State to U.S.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Ambassador to South Vietnam Henry Cabot Lodge Jr. stated that it was U.S. policy not to try to stop it.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Lucien Conein, the Central Intelligence Agency's liaison between the U.S.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Embassy and the coup planners, told them that the U.S. would not intervene to stop it.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Conein also provided 3 million Vietnamese piastres (approx. $42,000 USD) to reward military units that joined the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The decision to support the coup stemmed from the Kennedy administration's growing conviction that Diem was incapable of uniting the South Vietnamese people against communism.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diem's government was also increasingly seen as repressive, particularly after his violent crackdown on Buddhist protests.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The coup was led by General Dương Văn Minh and started on 1 November 1963.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] It proceeded smoothly, for many loyalist leaders were captured after being caught off-guard, and casualties were light.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diệm was captured and assassinated the next day, along with his brother and advisor Ngô Đình Nhu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diệm's road to political power began on 16 June 1954, when former emperor Bảo Đại, serving as Head of State, appointed him Prime Minister of the State of Vietnam in recognition of his strong anti-communist and anti-colonialist stance.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] He accepted the position of Prime Minister because on June 4th, France recognized the complete independence of the State of Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The two, however, became embroiled in a power struggle after Vietnam was divided in July.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The issue was brought to a head when Diệm scheduled a referendum for October 1955, which was rigged by his brother Nhu, and proclaimed himself the President of the newly created Republic of Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] He proceeded to strengthen his autocratic and nepotistic rule over the country.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] A rubber-stamp legislature wrote a constitution that gave Diệm the power to create laws by decree and arbitrarily give himself emergency powers.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Dissidents, both communist and nationalist, were jailed and executed in the thousands, and elections were routinely rigged.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Opposition candidates were threatened with being charged for conspiring with the North Vietnamese People's Army of Vietnam, which carried the death penalty, and in many areas, large numbers of Army of the Republic of Vietnam (ARVN) troops were sent to stuff ballot boxes.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diệm kept the control of the nation firmly within the hands of his family, and promotions in the ARVN were given on the basis of loyalty rather than merit.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Two unsuccessful attempts were made to depose Diệm; in 1960, a paratrooper revolt was quashed after Diệm stalled for negotiations to buy time for loyalists to put down the coup attempt, while a 1962 palace bombing by two Republic of Vietnam Air Force (RVNAF) pilots failed to kill him.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] By 1963, many but not the majority of Buddhists in South Vietnam had grown resentful of Diệm's perceived favoritism toward Catholics.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Allegedly, public servants had been promoted on the basis of religious preference, and government contracts, land, and business favors were preferentially given to Catholics.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The Catholic Church was the largest landowner in the country, and its holdings were exempt from land reform (i.e., appropriation).
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In the countryside, Catholics were *de facto* exempt from performing corvée labor.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In 1957, Diệm dedicated the nation to the Virgin Mary.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Discontent with Diệm and Nhu exploded into mass protest during mid-1963 when nine Buddhists died at the hand of Diệm's army and police on Vesak, the birthday of Gautama Buddha.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In response, the US government was concerned that it might be "impossible for the Diem/Nhu government to succeed and for us [the United States] to continue to support them".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The response by Ambassador Frederick Nolting was, "We should take it slow and easy and see if we can live with the Diem government." As a result of this potential inability to support the Diem/Nhu government, the United States government discussed a proposed coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In a telegram to the American Embassy in Saigon, U.S.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In May 1963, a law against the flying of religious flags was selectively enforced; the Buddhist flag was banned from display on Vesak, while the Vatican flag was displayed to celebrate the anniversary of the consecration of Archbishop Pierre Martin Ngô Đình Thục, Diệm's brother.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Many Buddhists defied the ban and a protest was ended when government forces opened fire.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] With Diệm remaining intransigent in the face of escalating Buddhist demands for religious equality, sections of society began calling for his removal from power.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The key turning point came shortly after midnight on 21 August, when Nhu's ARVN Special Forces raided and vandalized Buddhist pagodas across the country, arresting thousands of monks and causing a death toll estimated to be in the hundreds.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Numerous coup plans had been explored by the army before, but the plotters intensified their activities with increased confidence after the administration of US President John F.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Kennedy authorized the US embassy to explore the possibility of a leadership change through Cable 243.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] They felt Diệm's policies were making their allied regime in Vietnam politically unsustainable.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] There were many conspiracies against Diệm in 1963, many by different cliques of military officers independent from one another.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] According to the historian Ellen Hammer, there were "perhaps as many as six and possibly more" different plots, and these spanned the gamut of society to include civilian politicians, union leaders, and university students.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In mid-1963, one group was composed of mid-level officers such as colonels, majors, and captains.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Colonel Đỗ Mậu, director of military security, was in this group, which was coordinated by Trần Kim Tuyến, South Vietnam's director of intelligence.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Tuyến had been a palace insider, but a rift had developed in recent years, and he began plotting as early as 1962.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] As South Vietnam was a police state, Tuyến was a powerful figure and had many contacts.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Another person in this group was Colonel Phạm Ngọc Thảo, an undetected communist agent who was deliberately fomenting infighting among the officers and mismanaging the Strategic Hamlet Program in order to destabilise the Saigon government.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] These officers included commanders of airborne, marine and tank units from the 5th Division, mostly at battalion level.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] When Tuyến's machinations were uncovered, he was exiled by Nhu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Mậu and Thảo took over but their initial coup plans for 15 July were shelved when American CIA officer Lucien Conein instructed Thảo's superior, General Trần Thiện Khiêm, the head of the ARVN, to stop the coup on the grounds that it was premature.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Thảo and Mậu's group resumed plotting, intending to move on 24 October and they recruited a total of 3000 men.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] They augmented their forces with an assortment of officers from auxiliary units such as from the Signal Corps, Transportation Corps and some RVNAF pilots.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Mậu enlisted the help of Khiêm following Tuyến's departure into exile.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Mậu gained the cooperation of an assortment of military and civilian dissidents known as the Military and Civilian Front for the Revolution in Vietnam (MCFRV).
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The MCFRV had started to plot independently in August and their leader was a cousin of Mậu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Thảo's 24 October coup was canceled after senior officers decided that their younger colleagues could not succeed without the help of General Tôn Thất Đính, a loyalist who controlled the III Corps.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The generals sabotaged the younger officers by ordering one of their key regiments into the countryside to fight the communists.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The younger officers' plot was integrated into the generals' larger group, and because Khiêm and Mậu were involved with both groups.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] After the coup was completed, the media learned that the conspiracy organised by Tuyến and Thảo had been more advanced than that of the generals' before the latter were integrated into the main plot.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] General Trần Văn Đôn threatened to have the younger officers arrested but Mậu intervened to protect them.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Following the Xá Lợi Pagoda raids, the senior generals started their own plot in earnest, having only had vague plans prior to this.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] General Đôn, nominally a high-ranking general, but in a position without command of troops since the palace distrusted him, was sought out by Mậu, who wanted to collaborate.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Mậu later accompanied the ranking general in the plot, Dương Văn Minh, on recruitment campaigns.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Despite his high rank, Minh was out of favour and served as the Presidential Military Advisor, a meaningless desk job where he had no subordinates in the field and no access to soldiers.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Mậu helped Minh to secure the cooperation of General Nguyễn Khánh, who commanded the II Corps that oversaw the Central Highlands of the country, and Colonel Nguyễn Văn Thiệu, who commanded the 5th Division based just outside the capital in Biên Hòa.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] According to Thiệu, Mậu and Minh had promised to establish a more strongly anti-communist government and to keep Diệm as a figurehead president.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The generals knew that without the cooperation of General Đính, a coup would be difficult as his III Corps forces oversaw the region surrounding the capital.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Đính privately claimed responsibility for the pagoda attacks, stating to a journalist, "I have defeated Henry Cabot Lodge [the US ambassador to South Vietnam].
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] He came here to stage a *coup d'état*, but I, Tôn Thất Đính, have conquered him and saved the country." During this period, Đính claimed he was "a great national hero".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] His ego had been played upon by the Ngô brothers, who reiterated this point and paid him a large cash bonus after the pagoda raids.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In the heady times after the attacks, Đính told his American advisors that "he was without doubt the greatest general officer in the ARVN, the saviour of Saigon ... and soon he would be the top military man in the country".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In a press conference soon after, Đính claimed to have saved South Vietnam from "foreign adventurers", a euphemism for the United States.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] After being questioned sharply, Đính quickly became angry.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Ray Herndon of United Press International (UPI) asked him to name the country that he was referring to, but Đính dodged the question.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Herndon lampooned him by saying that a national hero should be able to identify the national enemy, and asked him to call Madame Nhu, the country's First Lady known for her anti-American comments, to get help in identifying the hostile country in question.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] After several reporters derisively laughed at his comments, Đính angrily stormed out of the conference hurling vulgarities at the newsmen in both English and Vietnamese.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Đính returned to the officers' mess at the Joint General Staff (JGS) headquarters and his colleagues attempted to play on Đính's ego to convince him to join their plot.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In a series of meetings, the other generals assured Đính that he was a national hero worthy of political authority, and claimed that Nhu had not realised how important he was in the future of the country. Đính's colleagues even bribed his soothsayer to predict his elevation to political power.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The other generals told him that the people were dissatisfied with Diệm's cabinet and that Vietnam needed dynamic young officers in politics, and that their presence would reverse the declining morale in the ARVN.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] They advised Đính to ask Diệm to promote him to Interior Minister, Dương Văn Minh to Defence Minister, and Trần Văn Minh to Education Minister.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Đính and his fellow generals met Diệm at the palace, where Đính asked the president to promote him to the post of Interior Minister.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diệm bluntly chastised Đính in front of his colleagues, and ordered him out of Saigon to the Central Highlands resort town of Đà Lạt to rest. Đính was humiliated and embarrassed, having promised his colleagues he would be successful.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Without Đính's troops, the coup would not have been possible.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] By mid-October, Diệm and Nhu were aware that a group of ARVN generals and colonels were planning a coup, but did not know that Đính was firmly among them, although they grew wary of him after his request for a cabinet post.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Nhu then made a plan to outwit the generals with a counter-plot.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The generals heard of this, and decided that they had to counteract him.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The other generals were still suspicious of Đính and whether he would betray them to the palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Having found out that Đính would be recruited for Nhu's plan, and not sure which side he was really on, they promised to make him Interior Minister and other rewards if they helped to overthrow the Ngô family.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Having gained a reassurance from Đính, the generals placated the younger officers, whose coup had been integrated into their plans.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Exhorting them to join the coup on the grounds that Diệm's regime was unable to keep the military going forward, he stated that all the generals except Cao were in the plot, while Đính was going to do so.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] According to one account, Đính intended for loyalists to report Có's activities to Diệm and Nhu so that it would give him an opportunity to orchestrate a stunt to ingratiate himself with the palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Nhu's agents heard of the conversation and reported to the palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] When the Ngô brothers confronted Đính with the report of what had happened in Mỹ Tho, Đính feigned astonishment at his deputy's behaviour.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Đính claimed to know nothing of Có's activities, raising his voice, vowing to have his deputy killed.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Nhu opposed this and stated that he wanted Có alive to catch the plotters, and tried to use Đính to achieve this.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Despite their distrust of Đính, the Ngô brothers told them this was not the case and that they would promote him.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Nhu ordered Đính and Tung, both of whom took their orders directly from the palace instead of the ARVN command, to plan a fake coup against the Ngô family.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] One of Nhu's objectives was to trick dissidents into joining the false uprising so that they could be identified and eliminated.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Another objective of the public relations stunt was to give the public a false impression of the strength of the Ngô regime.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Codenamed "Operation Bravo", the first stage of the scheme would involve some of Tung's loyalist soldiers, disguised as insurgents led by apparently renegade junior officers, faking a coup and vandalising the capital.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] During the orchestrated chaos of the first coup, the disguised loyalists would riot and in the ensuing mayhem, kill the leading coup plotters, such as Generals Dương Văn Minh, Trần Văn Đôn, Lê Văn Kim and junior officers that were helping them.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The loyalists and some of Nhu's underworld connections were also to kill some figures who were assisting the conspirators, such as the titular but relatively powerless Vice President Nguyễn Ngọc Thơ, CIA agent Lucien Conein, who was on assignment in South Vietnam as a military adviser, and Lodge.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Buddhist and student dissident leaders would also be targeted.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] These would be blamed on "neutralist and pro-communist elements".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Tung would then announce the formation of a "revolutionary government" consisting of opposition activists who had not consented to being named in the government, while Diệm and Nhu would pretend to be on the run and move to Vũng Tàu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] A fake "counter-coup" was to follow, whereby Tung's men, having left Saigon on the pretext of fighting the Viet Cong (VC), as well as Đính's forces, would triumphantly re-enter Saigon to reaffirm the Diệm regime.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Nhu would then round up opposition figures.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Đính, now a double agent, was put in charge of the fake coup and was allowed the additional control of the 7th Division, which was previously assigned to Diệm loyalist General Huỳnh Văn Cao, who was in charge of the IV Corps in the Mekong Delta.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The reassignment of the 7th Division to Đính gave his III Corps complete encirclement of Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The encirclement would prevent Cao from storming the capital to save Diệm as he had done during the 1960 coup attempt.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] This arrangement was supposed to make Đính's task of serving the regime easier, but it was exploited to bring down the Ngô family.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Nhu and Tung remained unaware of Đính's allegiance to the rebels, and were fooled. Đính told Tung that the fake coup needed to employ an overwhelming amount of force.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] He said that tanks were required "because armour is dangerous". Đính said that fresh troops were needed in the capital, opining, "If we move reserves into the city, the Americans will be angry.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] They'll complain that we're not fighting the war.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] So we must camouflage our plan by sending the special forces out to the country.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] That will deceive them." Nhu had no idea that Đính's real intention was to engulf Saigon with rebel units and lock Tung's loyalists in the countryside where they could not defend the Ngôs.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Nhu's coup would take place on 1 November, All Saints' Day, when Catholics prepare for All Souls' Day, which is the following day.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] This was so that troops could move freely through the streets, which would be carrying less traffic.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The generals decided to start their real coup on the same day to try to exploit Đính's liaison with Nhu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Colonel Đỗ Mậu, one of the conspirators, concocted military intelligence reports with false data that claimed that the VC were massing outside the capital for an offensive.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] He convinced Diệm and Nhu to send the special forces out of the capital to fight the VC.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Tung and Nhu agreed to send all four Saigon-based special forces companies out of Saigon on 29 October.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Another of Diệm's brothers, Ngô Đình Cẩn, began to suspect Mậu and told the palace, which told army chief General Khiêm to have Mậu arrested.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] However, Khiêm, who was also part of the plot, deliberately procrastinated, and Mậu remained free.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In the meantime, it was too late for the brothers to bring their loyalists back into the capital.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Not trusting Có, Diệm put Colonel Lâm Văn Phát in command of the 7th Division on 31 October.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] According to tradition, Phát had to pay the Corps' commander a courtesy visit before assuming control of the division. Đính refused to see Phát and told him to come back on Friday at 14:00, by which time the coup would have been in progress.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In the meantime, Đính had Đôn sign a counter-order transferring command of the 7th Division to Có.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The insurgent plans were based on three main task forces.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The first consisted of two battalions of marines and a company of M113 armored personnel carriers (APCs).
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Two battalions of airborne troops regarded as being pro-Diệm were moved to Bình Dương Province to the north of the capital and replaced with the two marine battalions.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The marines and the paratroopers were South Vietnam's strategic reserve and were usually deployed near Saigon for protecting the regime against any coups.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Another task force consisted of the 6th Airborne Battalion, which was based in Vũng Tàu around 70 km southwest of the capital, and a trainee battalion, supplemented by 12 APCs from the armor school at Long Hải.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The final task force consisted of the 2nd Battalion, 9th Regiment and the 2nd Battalion, 7th Regiment of the 5th Division of Colonel Thiệu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The troops involved in the operations in Saigon began preparing to move into the capital on the evening before the coup and in the early morning.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The second task force moved in from the southeast and converged with the other two moving in from the north, and some rebel elements from the 7th Division from the southwest.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] By noon, thousands of rebel soldiers had assembled on the city's outskirts, checking equipment and weapons and receiving last-minute orders.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Three marine battalions in tanks and armored cars had moved toward the Saigon city center to spearhead the revolt, and some of the 7th Division had arrived from the Mekong Delta to cut the main road from the south into Tân Sơn Nhứt Air Base.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The enlisted men did not know the truth behind their mission, nor did many lower-ranking officers; the senior officers told them that they were crushing a police revolt.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] One airborne lieutenant was suspicious, and as they moved into the suburbs, a colonel revealed that their objective was the Cộng Hòa barracks of the Presidential Guard.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] When the lieutenant asked "Who is the enemy and who our friend?", the colonel retorted that "Anyone who opposes us is the enemy".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The task forces were used to man various parts of the city, guarding the howitzers to be used in the siege of loyalist installations, and to protect the headquarters of Colonel Thiệu. Đính had 20 tanks brought to his III Corps headquarters at Camp Lê Văn Duyệt.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In all, the conspirators had 40 tanks and armoured personnel carriers.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] At 10:00 on 1 November, Lodge, Military Assistance Command, Vietnam (MACV) commander General Paul D.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Felt, the commander of US forces in the Pacific region, were invited to Gia Long Palace by Diệm. Đôn had scheduled the meeting for the visiting Felt at that time to keep Diệm occupied as the troops were moved in and to keep the president in Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] They were accompanied by Đôn, whose desk job meant that his duties consisted mainly of meeting visiting military dignitaries.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diệm gave one of his chain-smoking monologues and said that he would cooperate with US recommendations.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] According to Lodge, however, Diệm was more direct and to the point than usual.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diệm recounted to Felt about the Ngô family's achievements, then complained about American aid cuts in response to the pagoda raids.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] He blamed the generals, claiming they had attacked the Buddhists, not the special forces, and claimed Tung's men were now under ARVN control and not used as a private army, which was false.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diệm also claimed that aid cutbacks had hindered the army and led to food shortages.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] At one stage, Diệm said "I know there is going to be a coup attempt, but I don't know who is going to do it", to which Lodge purportedly replied "I don't think that there is anything to worry about".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diệm then asked Lodge to talk to officials in Washington about Nhu's future; Diệm was still refusing to remove his brother from authority.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] He said "Please tell President Kennedy I am a good and frank ally, that I would rather be frank and settle questions than talk about them after we have lost everything.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Tell President Kennedy that I take all his suggestions very seriously and wish to carry them out but it is a question of timing." Lodge did not discuss anything specific with regards to a regime change, but claimed that he was not worried by rumors that Diệm and Nhu had wanted to assassinate him.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Lodge expressed his "admiration and personal friendship" and gratitude for Diệm's hospitality.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] As Harkins and Felt prepared to leave, Diệm took Lodge aside for an individual discussion and repeatedly asked what the Americans wanted, repeating his request for 20 minutes.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] This was a trick on Diệm's part, for the fake coup was about to begin.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] In reference to a United Nations inquiry over his repression of the Buddhists, Diệm claimed that Buddhists had been brainwashed by the Americans.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Diệm claimed he had closed the pagodas because among the students were communists about to throw grenades and perpetrate bombings during the UN visit.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The president also claimed that some Americans were planning a coup against him and promised to give Lodge names.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The American ambassador replied with a poker face that he was committed to removing any of his countrymen who were involved in plotting, even though he was doing so himself.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Lodge was not taken in by Diệm, as Washington had already told Diệm what reforms were necessary, such as the removal of Nhu and the use of the special forces to fight communists rather than dissidents; Diệm had not responded to US advice.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Lodge knew that the real coup was in the offing and did not want to stop it, even if Diệm's overtures were genuine.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Felt was unaware of impending events—as was Harkins—and hurried to Tân Sơn Nhứt Air Base for his noon flight.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Before leaving, he held a press conference with Harkins and Đôn while the rebels were rolling into the city.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Harkins spoke about the military situation with optimism; on the morning of the coup, the front page of the *Stars and Stripes*, a military newspaper, featured a piece with Harkins' sunny outlook, entitled "Viet Victory Near".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] While Felt and Harkins were talking, the officers were preparing to launch the coup at a lunchtime meeting at military headquarters next to the airport.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Thinking of the situation, Đôn kept glancing at his watch while waiting for Felt to fly out.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The three men were standing as they talked, and Đôn, overcome by nerves, chewed his gum "like a threshing machine", and could not stand still, frequently changing his footing as he talked.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] After Felt left, the runway was closed, and Đôn brushed off Harkins and quickly went away to get ready for the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Up to the last minute, Harkins and Felt remained unaware of the imminent coup, despite Đôn's fidgety behaviour.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The pair had paid a visit to Đôn to discuss military issues at 09:15, but instead of the Vietnamese general hosting his American visitors at JGS headquarters, as was the norm, Đôn went to the MACV office.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Although Felt was surprised, the Americans did not realise the reason for the unusual venue and then pointed at a map and wondered why two airborne battalions appeared to be idling. Đôn replied that they were going into battle, and Harkins nodded, unaware that they were entering Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Harkins had told the generals earlier that he opposed a coup, so Đôn avoided the topic.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Felt had been told of the existence of coup plans by Lodge, who falsely informed him that such action was not imminent, saying "There isn't a Vietnamese general with hair enough on his chest to make it go." Felt later said that Đôn appeared to be calm and composed.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] On the morning of the coup, there was still some trepidation among the plotters.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Khiêm approached Đính and asked him to keep their conversation confidential.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] After the III Corps commander agreed, Khiêm claimed that he wanted to cancel the coup, saying "Đính, I think we still have time to talk to the old man.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Have pity on him!" Đính contemplated the situation and said that he would still proceed with the overthrow.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Khiêm reported this to Đôn, and claimed that he had placed Chinese medicinal oil into his eyes to irritate and redden them and thus give the appearance he had become remorseful about the coup, in order to test Đính's loyalty to the plot.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Both Minh and Đôn were wary of Khiêm and Đính up to the last minute, as the latter were both Catholics who were favourites of the Ngô family, who had been rewarded for their loyalty, rather than competence.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The other generals remained worried that Đính might switch sides and go through with the second part of Nhu's fake coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The generals were also concerned that they would not have enough forces to overcome the loyalists.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The first victim of the coup was Captain Hồ Tấn Quyền, Diệm's loyalist Republic of Vietnam Navy (RVNN) commander, who was shot dead on his 36th birthday before noon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] There are varying accounts of Quyền's death.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] According to Stanley Karnow, Quyền had noticed abnormal troop movements and drove off to discuss the matter with a colleague.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] A jeep of rebel marines followed and intercepted him by overtaking him and blocking the road.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Quyền abandoned his vehicle and ran across the open field, but stumbled and fell with the marines in hot pursuit.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] One of them reached him and shot him in the head point blank.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] According to Ellen Hammer, however, Quyền started his birthday with an early morning tennis match with fellow officers, who invited him to a lunchtime birthday party.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Quyền declined in order to look after his children who were at home alone while his wife was studying in Japan.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] His deputy, who was part of the plot, followed him home and managed to change Quyền's mind.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The two men headed for a restaurant on Saigon's outskirts, and the shooting took place along the way.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Historian and author Mark Moyar wrote that Quyền noticed suspicious troop movements near the capital in the morning.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] As Quyền prepared to go to the palace to alert the Ngô brothers, his deputy shot him dead on the Biên Hòa highway.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The generals were immediately informed of the killing and forced to bring forward intended troop movements into Saigon ahead of schedule.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] On 1 November, the plotters summoned many senior officers who were not involved in the plot to the JGS headquarters at Tân Sơn Nhứt, on the pretext of a routine lunchtime leadership meeting.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Mậu and Đôn organised the invitations and set up the trap.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] At 13:45, Đôn announced that a coup was taking place.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Most of the officers rose to applaud, while those who did not and refused to turn against Diệm were brutally beaten and arrested by their colleagues.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The plotters neutralized many Diệm loyalists in this manner, most notably Colonel Tung, who was brutally beaten and arrested by Captain Nguyễn Văn Nhung, Minh's bodyguard.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] During the early stages of the coup, the rebels forced Tung to order his men to surrender by putting a pistol to his head and forcing him to make a phone call to his subordinates.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] This meant that only the Presidential Guard was left to defend Gia Long Palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] At 16:45, Tung was forced at gunpoint to talk to Diệm on the phone, telling the president that he had told his men to stand down, but Tung failed to convince the president to surrender.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Minh then ordered Nhung to execute Tung as he still commanded the loyalty of his men.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The other generals had little sympathy for the special forces commander as he had disguised his men in army uniforms and framed the generals for the pagoda raids.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The generals were well aware of the threat that Tung posed; they had discussed and agreed on his elimination during their planning, having contemplated waging an offensive against Tung's special forces.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] At nightfall Tung was taken with Major Lé Quang Trieu, his brother and deputy, hands tied, into a jeep and driven to the edge of the air base.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Forced to kneel over two freshly dug holes, the brothers were shot into their graves and buried.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Another leading officer who stayed loyal to Diệm was Colonel Cao Văn Viên, commander of the airborne brigade.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Viên had been unaware of the plot, and the generals had discussed whether to assassinate him during their planning phase because they knew he was a Diệmist.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] However, Đính, who played mahjong with Viên's wife, convinced Minh to not have Viên liquidated, and promised that Viên would not oppose the coup. Đính's prediction that Viên would acquiesce was incorrect.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Viên "broke down completely" and took off his insignia and handed it to Minh in resignation.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] He was then brutally beaten and arrested, and subsequently sentenced to death.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Viên had planned with Diệm to allow the president to take refuge at his home in the event of a coup, but the offer was moot as rebels surrounded Viên's house after taking him into custody.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Viên narrowly avoided execution and was released and returned to command after the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] General Khang, the commander of the marine brigade, was also brutally beaten and arrested for remaining loyal to Diệm, as was the head of the RVNAF Đỗ Khắc Mai, and the National Police chief.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] After the loyalists were taken away, Minh read the coup proclamation and his objectives and taped it and asked the other officers to sign the papers.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] They then spoke into the recorder, identifying themselves as supporters of the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Minh told his subordinates to have copies made of the original, and hid the copies in several places so that his accomplices could not claim that they were not involved if the putsch failed.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Minh was to play them over the radio later that day.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] With a group of his personal rebel officers, Có flew by helicopter to Mỹ Tho, the division headquarters, to take command on the morning of the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Reaching the Mekong Delta town two hours before the scheduled start of the coup, he held a ceremony for the division's incumbent officers—who thought the change of command was a routine matter—in a local hall.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] When the coup started, Có's men charged through the doors with automatic weapons and arrested the officers, before taking command.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Anyone who rises will be instantly shot".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Có then phoned Cao, further south in the Mekong Delta's largest town Cần Thơ, where the IV Corps was headquartered.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] The rebel colonel assured Cao that the divisional and corps transfer had taken place smoothly.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Có, a central Vietnamese, was afraid that Cao, a Mekong Delta native, would recognise his fake southern accent, and realize that he was impersonating Phat, another southerner.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] When Cao was informed by his subordinates that there was a coup occurring in the capital, he believed it to be part of the false coup, as he had been told beforehand by Nhu; Cao was one of the regime's most loyal and favored generals and he was going to help stage the second part of Nhu's plan.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Cao told one regiments and a few tanks to ready themselves for the second part of the plot.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Later, Cao realised it was a genuine coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] He sent the 9th Division under Colonel Bùi Dzinh to move north through Mỹ Tho towards Saigon to save Diệm, but Có had already made plans to cut off any attempt by Cao to relieve Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] When Cao radioed the 7th Division in Mỹ Tho, Có identified himself and taunted the corps commander, saying "Didn't you recognise my accent?".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Có told the general that he had ordered all the ferries to the Saigon side of the Mekong River, and told Cao not to attempt to cross unless he wanted to die.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p01] Seeing that Diệm was lost, Cao later expressed solidarity with the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The rebels encountered little resistance at the start of the attack on Saigon, and this allowed them to generate momentum.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] This was primarily due to Diệm and Nhu's complacency and their mistaken assumption that the military action was the start of Operation Bravo.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The central police called Diệm, informing him that the marines did not appear to be friendly.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] It was too late as the rebels captured the police headquarters and shut down the secret police, which were directly controlled by Nhu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Wearing red scarves for identification, the rebel marines caught the loyalists off guard and took over control of the building of the Interior Ministry and the National Police headquarters.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The latter installation was captured by some newly enlisted troops from the Quang Trung National Training Center, led by General Mai Hữu Xuân, who promptly arrested the Diem supporters in the office.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The rebels also tried to take control of the Infantry School in Saigon so that they could use the two trainee battalions against Diệm, but the loyalist head of the institution, Colonel Lam Son, foiled their plans.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] One of Diệm's aides called Đính but was told that Đính was not there.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Diệm and Nhu remained relaxed, confident that it was the phony coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] When security officials noticed the troop movements, a panicked young officer telephoned Nhu, who serenely said.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] "It's all right, I know about it." The generals timed the coup to trick Nhu and Diệm, who were always paranoid about threats to their power, into believing that the threat was false.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The rebels outnumbered the Diệmists and quickly made inroads against the loyalists, who were caught unawares and confused about whether the coup was real.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh had decided to keep the loyalists in their rank afterward if they still wanted to fight the VC.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Most of the anti-Diệm forces also wanted to avoid killing the president in a large-scale battle for the palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The rebels quickly took control of Tân Sơn Nhứt to control air traffic, and set up checkpoints and defense installations on the cities' outskirts to guard against any counterattack that might come from outside the capital.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] They also blew up government buildings, and took control of the national post office and Radio Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Four RVNAF AD-6 fighter-bombers roared above the city centre, adding to the confusion and threatening loyalist positions.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lieutenant Colonel Nguyễn Cao Kỳ, the RVNAF deputy commander, sent two T-28 fighter-bombers over Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] They strafed the palace, and fired two rockets while avoiding sporadic black and white clouds of antiaircraft fire.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Both shots missed their targets, and the second struck an empty US Marine barracks.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] At the same time, some fighter-bombers made strafing runs at the RVNN headquarters in the capital, where the defenders remained loyal to Diệm.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Some anti-aircraft guns on the RVNN vessels patrolling in the Saigon River returned fire.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Around 15 minutes after the start of the coup, radio transmissions were taken off the air, severing communication with those outside Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Early on during the coup, while the special forces were still fighting before the generals forced Tung to order them to capitulate, one of his subordinates was in Gia Long Palace and made a proposal to Diệm.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] According to the diary of one of Diệm's aides, the special forces officer drew up and proposed a surprise counter-attack on the rebel headquarters at Tân Sơn Nhứt using loyalist infantry and tanks.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Tân Sơn Nhứt was located on the northwestern edge of the city, and the officer said that it was only protected by trainee soldiers.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] He told Diệm there was no chance that the new recruits could resist a loyalist attack and therefore the generals would be easily captured and the leadership of the coup would break down.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The aide reported that Diệm turned down the proposal, saying "The brigade should conserve its forces to fight the communists and avoid bloodshed.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] In the meantime, it should protect Gia Long Palace, the post office and the treasury." Another aide believed that Diệm did not want to attack the headquarters of the JGS because "it represented the authority of the armed forces" and to avoid "more harm, more death, more suffering for the soldiers".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] According to this account, Diệm "was confident that his forbearance would make the coup forces realize that he was a president who always stood on the side of the masses of the population".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] To stop the loyalist forces near the palace from escaping, armoured and artillery units commanded by Colonel Thiệu placed their tanks and howitzers shoulder-to-shoulder, in preparation for the shelling of the Cộng Hòa barracks of the Presidential Guard, located near the palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] APCs brought more rebel troops with machine guns to surround the Cộng Hòa Barracks, where the defenders were armed with artillery, mortars and machine guns.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Under the command of Thiệu, the siege of the barracks started, and rebel artillery shells soon reduced the buildings to rubble, but the pro-Diệm loyalists fought on, a scant five blocks from the palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Presidential Guard tanks returned fire, severely damaging nearby roadways.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] After an hour, Diệm and Nhu suspected that something was amiss and attempted to call Đính's office for a second time and again were told Đính was not there.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Not believing Đính had double-crossed them, the Ngô brothers were heard in the background speculating that Đính had been arrested by the rebels.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The generals then phoned Gia Long Palace with an ultimatum.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] If Diệm resigned immediately, he and Nhu would be safely exiled.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] If he did not, they would launch air strikes and start shelling the palace within the hour.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The generals said that there would be no negotiation, only a yes or no would be acceptable.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Shortly after 16:00, Diệm telephoned JGS headquarters. Đôn answered and stated "the time has come when the army must respond to the wishes of the people" because Diệm had failed to reform his leadership.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The pair had a robust argument and Diệm asked the commanders to visit him at the palace to negotiate and work on a reform plan.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The generals, remembering that he bought time for loyalists to come to his aid during the 1960 coup attempt by stalling the coup with talks and a false promise of reform and power-sharing, turned down his suggestion.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] At 16:30, the generals officially announced the coup over national radio, repeating the recorded message at five-minute intervals.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Their message called on Diệm and Nhu to give up power, and many officers identified themselves as participants.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The recorded pledges made at JGS were also played.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh said "The day the people have been waiting for has come.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] For eight years, the people of Vietnam have suffered under the rotten, nepotic Diem regime, but now the armed forces have come to their rescue." It further said "Soldiers in the army, security service, civil defense force, and people's force ...
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The Ngo Dinh Diem government, abusing power, has thought only of personal ambition and slighted the fatherland's interests ...
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The revolution will certainly be successful." The proclamation was endorsed by 14 generals, 7 colonels and a major.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] It further added that "We have no political ambitions ...
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] However, a technical malfunction interrupted the broadcasts with twist and cha-cha music; under the Diệm regime Madame Nhu had banned dancing and associated music under a series of "morality laws".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] In the meantime, RVNAF transport planes dropped rebel leaflets over Saigon, asking the population to rally to the anti-Diệm cause.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Concurrent to the generals' radio broadcast, Diệm telephoned Lodge at the US Embassy.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Diệm angrily shouted in French, and Lodge had to hold the receiver away from his ear.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Diệm's voice was loud enough that Lodge's aides could hear the message from a distance.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] It later emerged, however, that Lodge had not given a full account of the conversation to his superiors at the State Department.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Blair said "there can be no doubt that Lodge silenced some of Diệm's rejoinder, supremely confident as he was in his ability to control not only the American press but the official government records as well".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lodge's aide, Frederick Flott, claimed that in the middle of the conversation Lodge offered to send his staff to Diệm's palace to have the Ngô brothers taken to the airport and safely exiled and exhorted him to leave.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lodge wanted to send Flott to the palace in a taxi marked with American flags, to negotiate his way into the building and take the brothers to the airport, where he would be flown aboard an American aircraft to a military base in the Philippines.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Diệm mistakenly presumed that Lodge's offer implied American reinforcements against the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] One account from a US embassy official added the following passage, omitted by Lodge.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Through the afternoon and into the night, the loudspeakers on the grounds of Gia Long Palace carried Diệm's recorded exhortation to loyalists that "We shall not give in".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] These were mixed with passages of military music.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] At the same time, the US military ordered units of the Seventh Fleet to move into the waters near Saigon as a "precautionary measure" in case the fighting endangered American lives and to deter an opportunistic communist offensive.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Gia Long Palace, the presidential mansion, had once served as the home of French governor generals.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] For security reasons, the surrounding streets were regularly sealed after sunset; the building had several bunkers and an intricate tunnel system, including a half-block-long escape route to the basement of the City Hall.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] On the morning of 1 November, Diệm had reinforced palace security with more soldiers and barbed-wire barricades.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The palace was surrounded by walls of around 2.1 m, and defended by 150 troops of the Presidential Guard.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The building was protected by machine and antiaircraft guns and ringed with pillboxes, tanks, and 20-mm cannons mounted on armoured vehicles.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] As Diệm refused to surrender, vowing to reassert his control, after sunset, Thiệu led his 7th Division in an assault on Gia Long Palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] They used artillery and flamethrowers and it fell by daybreak after Diệm finally gave the order to the Presidential Guard to surrender.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The coup results pleased the anti-Diệmists.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The casualties were light: 9 insurgents killed and 46 wounded, 4 dead and 44 injured Presidential Guards.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The greatest casualties were from the populace, who suffered 20 deaths and 146 injured.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] When I Corps commander General Đỗ Cao Trí was informed that coup was imminent, he left Huế on 29 October for Đà Nẵng so that he would be away from Ngô Đình Cẩn, who ruled central Vietnam from Hue for his family.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The coup took place on 1 November, and Trí helped to prevent any loyalist actions by causing diversions.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] He scheduled a meeting with the province chief and other pro-Diệm officials during the time that the coup was to take place.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] As a result, Diệm loyalists were stuck in a meeting room and were unable to mobilise the Republican Youth and other Ngô family paramilitary and activist groups.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] In the early morning of 2 November 1963 Diệm agreed to surrender.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The ARVN officers had a meeting intended to exile Diệm and Nhu, having promised the Ngô brothers safe passage out of the country into an "honorable retirement".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Not all of the senior officers attended the meeting.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] General Nguyễn Ngọc Lê strongly lobbied for Diệm's execution.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] There was no formal vote taken at the meeting, and Lê attracted only minority support.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Conein reported that the generals had never indicated that assassination was on their minds, since an orderly transition of power was a high priority in achieving their ultimate aim of gaining international recognition.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh and Don asked Conein to secure an American aircraft to take the brothers out of the country.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Two days earlier, Lodge had alerted Washington that such a request was likely and recommended Saigon as the departure point.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] This request put the Kennedy administration in a difficult position, as the provision of an airplane would publicly tie it to the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] When Conein telephoned the Saigon CIA station, there was a ten-minute wait.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The US government would not allow the aircraft to land in any country, unless that state was willing to grant asylum to Diem.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] If the generals decide to exile Diem, he should also be sent outside Southeast Asia." He further went on to anticipate what he termed a "Götterdämmerung in the palace".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] After surrendering, Diệm rang Lodge and spoke to the American envoy for the last time.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lodge did not report the conversation to Washington, so it was widely assumed that the pair last spoke on the previous afternoon when the coup was just starting.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] However, after Lodge died in 1985, his aide, Colonel Mike Dunn, said that Lodge and Diệm spoke for the last time at around 07:00 on 2 November, moments after Diệm surrendered.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] When Diệm called, Lodge "put [him] on hold" and then walked away.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Upon his return, the ambassador offered Diệm and Nhu asylum, but would not arrange for transportation to the Philippines until the next day.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] This contradicted his earlier offer of asylum the previous day when he implored Diệm not to resist the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Dunn then offered to personally go to the brothers' hideout to escort him so that the generals could not kill him, but Lodge refused, saying "We just can't get that involved".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Dunn said "I was really astonished that we didn't do more for them".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Having refused to help the Ngô brothers to leave the country safely, Lodge later said after they had been shot: "What would we have done with them if they had lived?
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Dunn claimed Lodge put Diệm on hold to inform Conein where the brothers were—they had sneaked out of the palace so that the generals could capture them.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] When confronted about Dunn's claim by a historian, Conein denied the account.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] One of Lodge's staff told Conein that the plane would have to go directly to the faraway asylum-offering country, so that the brothers could not disembark at a nearby stopover country and stay there to foment a counter-coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Conein was told that the nearest plane that was capable of such a long range flight was in Guam, and it would take 24 hours to make the necessary arrangements.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh was astounded and told Conein that the generals could not hold Diệm for that long.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Conein reportedly did not suspect a deliberate delay by the American embassy.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh traveled to Gia Long Palace in a sedan with his aide and bodyguard, Captain Nhung to arrest the Ngô brothers.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh had also dispatched an APC and four jeeps to Gia Long to transport Diệm and Nhu back to JGS headquarters for the ceremonial handover of power during a nationally televised event witnessed by international media.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Diệm and Nhu would then "ask" the generals to be granted exile and asylum in a foreign country, which would be granted.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh instead arrived to find that the brothers were missing.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] In anticipation of a coup, they had ordered the construction of three separate tunnels leading from Gia Long to remote areas outside the palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] At around 20:00 on the previous night, Diệm and Nhu hurriedly packed American banknotes into a briefcase.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] They escaped through one of the tunnels with two loyalists: Cao Xuân Vy, head of Nhu's Republican Youth, and RVNAF Lieutenant Đỗ Thơ, Diệm's aide-de-camp, who happened to be a nephew of Đỗ Mậu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Diệm and Nhu emerged in a wooded area in a park near the Cercle Sportif (10°46′34″N 106°41′35″E﻿ / ﻿10.776°N 106.693°E﻿ / 10.776; 106.693), the city's upper-class sporting club, where they were picked up by a waiting vehicle.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Historian Ellen Hammer disputes the tunnel escape, asserting that the Ngô brothers simply walked out of the building, which was not yet under siege.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Hammer asserts that they walked past the tennis courts and left the palace grounds through a small gate at Le Thanh Ton Street and entered the car.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The loyalists traveled through narrow back streets in order to evade rebel checkpoints and changed vehicles to a black Citroën sedan.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] After leaving the palace, Nhu was reported to have suggested to Diệm that the brothers split up, arguing this would enhance their chances of survival.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Nhu proposed that one of them travel to the Mekong Delta to join Cao's IV Corps, while the other would travel to the II Corps of General Khánh in the Central Highlands.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Nhu felt that the rebel generals would not dare to kill one of them while the other was free, in case the surviving brother was to regain power.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] According to one account, Diệm reportedly turned down Nhu, reasoning that "You cannot leave alone.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] They hate you too much; they will kill you.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Stay with me and I will protect you." Another story holds that Diệm reportedly said "We have always been together during these last years.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] How could we separate during these last years?
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] How could we separate in this critical hour?" Nhu agreed that they should stay together until the end.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The loyalists reached the home of Ma Tuyen in the Chinese business district of Cholon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Ma Tuyen was a Chinese merchant and friend who was reported to be Nhu's main contact with the Chinese syndicates which controlled the opium trade.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The brothers sought asylum from the embassy of the Republic of China, but were turned down and stayed in Ma Tuyen's house as they appealed to ARVN loyalists and attempted to negotiate with the coup leaders.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Nhu's secret agents had fitted the home with a direct phone line to the palace, so the insurgent generals believed that the brothers were still besieged inside Gia Long.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Neither the rebels nor the loyalist Presidential Guard had any idea that at 21:00 they were about to fight for an empty building, leading to futile deaths.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh was reported to be mortified when he realised that Diệm and Nhu had escaped in the middle of the night.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] After Minh had ordered the rebels to search the areas known to have been frequented by the Ngô family, Colonel Phạm Ngọc Thảo was informed by a captured Presidential Guard officer that the brothers had escaped through the tunnels to a refuge in Cholon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Thảo was told by Khiêm to find and prevent Diệm from being killed.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] When Thảo arrived at Ma Tuyen's house, he phoned his superiors.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Diệm and Nhu overheard him and fled to the nearby Catholic Church of St.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The Ngô brothers walked through the shady courtyard.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] It was speculated that they were recognised by an informant while they walked through the yard.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] A few minutes later, just after 10:00, an APC and two jeeps entered.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The convoy was led by General Mai Hữu Xuân and consisted of Colonels Quan and Lắm.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Quan was Minh's deputy, and Lắm was commander of Diệm's Civil Guard.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lắm had joined the coup once a rebel victory seemed assured.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Two further officers made up the convoy: Major Dương Hiếu Nghĩa and Captain Nhung, Minh's bodyguard.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Nhu expressed disgust that they were to be transported in an APC, asking "You use such a vehicle to drive the president?" Lắm assured them the armor was for their own protection.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Xuân told them it was selected to protect them from "extremists".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The brothers' hands were tied behind their backs..
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] After the arrest, Nhung and Nghĩa sat with the brothers in the APC, and the convoy departed for Tân Sơn Nhứt.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Before the convoy departed for the church, Minh reportedly gestured to Nhung with two fingers, which some have claimed was to be taken as an order to kill both brothers.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The convoy stopped at a railroad crossing on the return trip, where by all accounts the brothers were killed.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] An investigation by Đôn later determined that Nghia had shot the brothers at point-blank range with a semi-automatic firearm and that Nhung sprayed them with bullets before repeatedly stabbing the bodies with a knife.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] When the corpses arrived at JGS headquarters, the generals were shocked.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lodge later concluded that "Once again, brother Nhu proves to be the evil genius in Diệm's life." Đôn ordered another general to tell reporters that the brothers had died in an accident.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] At this time, Xuân walked into Minh's office through the open door, unaware of Đôn's presence.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Xuân snapped to attention and stated "*Mission accomplie*".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Shortly afterward, the CIA sent word to the White House that Diệm and Nhu were dead, allegedly due to suicide.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Vietnam Radio had announced their deaths by poison, and that they had committed suicide while in the APC.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Unclear and contradictory stories abounded.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] General Harkins reported that the suicides had occurred either by gunshot or by a grenade wrestled from the belt of an ARVN officer who was standing guard.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh tried to explain the discrepancy by saying "Due to an inadvertence, there was a gun inside the vehicle.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] When Kennedy learned of the deaths during a White House meeting, he appeared shaken, and left the room.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Kennedy later penned a memo, lamenting that the assassination was "particularly abhorrent" and blaming himself for approving Cable 243, which authorised Lodge to explore coup options in the wake of Nhu's Xá Lợi Pagoda raids.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Kennedy's reaction did not draw unanimous sympathy.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Through Conein, the Americans later became aware of the true reasons for the deaths of Diệm and Nhu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Later, photos appeared showing the two dead brothers covered in blood on the floor of the APC.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The images appeared to be genuine, discrediting the generals' claims that the brothers had committed suicide.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Once the news of the cause of death of the Ngô brothers began to become public, the US became concerned at its association with the new junta and began asking questions.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lodge initially backed the false story disseminated by the generals, believing that the brothers had shot themselves.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Several members of the Kennedy administration were appalled by the killings, citing them as a key factor in the future leadership troubles which beset South Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The assassinations caused a split within the leadership of the junta, and repulsed American and world opinion.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The killings damaged the public belief that the new regime would be an improvement over the Ngô family, turning the initial harmony among the generals into discord.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The criticism of the killings caused the officers to distrust and battle one another for positions in the new government.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The responsibility for the assassinations was generally put on the shoulders of Minh.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lodge thought Xuân was partly culpable, asserting that "Diệm and Nhu had been assassinated, if not by Xuân personally, at least at his direction." Minh later blamed Thiệu for the assassinations.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] In 1971, Minh claimed Thiệu was responsible for the deaths by hesitating and delaying the attack by the 5th Division on Gia Long Palace.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Conein asserted that Minh's humiliation by the Ngô brothers was a major motivation for ordering their executions.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] He reasoned that Minh had been embarrassed by arriving at the presidential residence in full ceremonial military uniform to take power, only to find an empty building.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] One CIA employee said "They had to kill him [Diệm].
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Otherwise his supporters would gradually rally and organise and there would be civil war." Several months after the event, Minh reportedly said privately that "We had no alternative.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Diệm could not be allowed to live because he was too much respected among simple, gullible people in the countryside, especially the Catholics and the refugees.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Trần Văn Hương, a civilian opposition politician who was jailed in 1960 for signing the Caravelle Manifesto that criticised Diệm, said: "The top generals who decided to murder Diệm and his brother were scared to death.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The generals knew very well that having no talent, no moral virtues, no political support whatsoever, they could not prevent a spectacular comeback of the president and Mr.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The coup was immediately denounced by the Soviet Union and the People's Republic of China, asserting that the coup had brought a US "puppet" government.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The remainder of the world expressed the general hope that the junta would end persecution of Buddhists and focus on defeating the communist insurgency.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Both North Vietnam and the VC were caught off guard by the events in Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Hanoi initially did not comment apart from repeating the news, as they had not been prepared.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] On one hand, the communist leaders were disheartened that they could no longer exploit Diệm's unpopularity; on the other, they were confident that Diệm's successors would be weak, fall apart easily and facilitate a communist revolution.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The official newspaper, the *Nhan Dan*, opined that "By throwing off Ngo Dinh Diem and his brother Ngo Dinh Nhu, the US imperialists have themselves destroyed the political bases they had built up for years.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] On the night of 1 November, as Gia Long Palace was besieged, VC radio in South Vietnam had urged the Vietnamese people and ARVN loyalists to resist the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] However, the generals' quick and successful coup prevented any joint action.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Within a week of the coup, the VC had regained its direction and launched more than one thousand attacks.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] A communist spokesperson expressed shock that the Americans had appeared to support the removal of Diệm, believing him to have been one of their strongest opponents.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The leader of the VC, Nguyễn Hữu Thọ, termed the coup a "gift from Heaven for us".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Some VC officials were so surprised that the Americans would remove Diệm that they thought it was a trick.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] They felt Diệm's removal was a blunder on the part of the Americans.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The deposition of the Ngô brothers was greeted with widespread joy by the South Vietnamese public.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Large spontaneous street demonstrations took place.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The offices of the *Times of Vietnam*, the Ngô family's propaganda mouthpiece, were burned.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Elsewhere, the crowd smashed windows and ransacked any building associated with Nhu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The tension released by the downfall of the regime sparked off celebrations similar to Tết (Lunar New Year) celebrations.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Americans were treated and received with great enthusiasm, Lodge was mobbed by the Saigon public, and it was joked that Lodge would win any Vietnamese election by a landslide.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lodge recommended immediate recognition of the new regime by Washington, asserting that the popular approval of the Vietnamese for the coup warranted it.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Lodge reported: "Every Vietnamese has a grin on his face today".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The crowds swarmed onto the grounds of Gia Long Palace in a carnival atmosphere, punctuated by celebratory ARVN gunfire, while a sea of Buddhist flags flew throughout the city.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] As Lodge traveled from his residence to the US embassy, the crowds cheered his convoy, and when he walked past the Xá Lợi Pagoda, the focal point of the raids by Nhu's Special Forces, he was mobbed by jubilant Buddhists who tossed him high into the air several times until he was rescued by police.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The people were very happy with the soldiers, giving them fruit, flowers and garlands of roses.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Madame Nhu, who was in the United States at the time, denounced the coup and angrily accused the Americans of orchestrating it.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] When asked about whether the US was involved, she replied "definitely", elaborating that "no coup can erupt without American incitement and backing" and declaring that she would not seek asylum "in a country whose government stabbed me in the back".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] She said "I believe all the devils of hell are against us" and that "whoever has the Americans as allies does not need enemies".
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The United States publicly disclaimed responsibility or involvement in the coup.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Many, including Harriman, General Maxwell Taylor, and Assistant Secretary of State Roger Hilsman, denied involvement, although Hilsman admitted that American disapproval of Diem's policies would have encouraged the generals.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Privately, the White House was elated by the coup, as it had been relatively bloodless.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The White House fostered the impression that the coup was purely Vietnamese and claimed to have no knowledge of it.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] A year later, Trueheart was quoted that the United States had been aware of the generals' actions.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Even before the start of the coup, the generals had been in contact with civilian opposition figures and more moderate members of Diệm's regime.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Once the coup was confirmed to have concluded, negotiations by the generals and dissidents began.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] All of Diệm's ministers were forced to resign, and no further reprisals were taken.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Diệm's Vice President Nguyễn Ngọc Thơ had discussions with Minh over the interim government.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The Americans also pressured the generals to give Thơ a prominent role so as to give the impression of civilian rule.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] They promised to resume the Commercial Import Program, their main aid initiative to South Vietnam, which had been suspended due to relations with Diệm.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The Military Revolutionary Council (MRC), as it called itself, dissolved Diệm's rubber-stamp National Assembly and the constitution of 1956.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The MRC vowed support for free elections, unhindered political opposition, freedom of the press, freedom of religion, and an end to discrimination, and that the purpose of the coup was to bolster the fight against the VC.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Further, it condemned the recent legislative elections as "dishonest and fraudulent", imposed martial law, announced a curfew, and ordered the release of political prisoners jailed by Diệm.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The MRC also announced that a new constitution would be written.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] In the interim, an appointed body known as the "Council of Notables" replaced the legislature in an advisory capacity.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The generals decided on a two-tier government structure, with a military committee overseen by Minh presiding over a regular cabinet that would be predominantly civilian, with Thơ as prime minister.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The new government was announced on 5 November.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh was named president and chief of the Military Committee; Thơ was listed as prime minister, Minister of Economy, and Minister of Finance; Đôn was named Minister of Defense; and Đính was made the Minister of Security (Interior).
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Only one other general was in the cabinet of 15, which was dominated by bureaucrats and civilians with no previous political experience.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] This was followed by the release of Provisional Constitutional Act No.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] 1, formally suspending the 1956 constitution and detailing the structure and duty of the interim government.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] On 6 November, Saigon radio announced the composition of the executive committee of the MRC.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] Minh was chairman, Đính and Đôn were deputy chairmen, and nine other senior generals, including Kim, Thiệu, Khiêm, Trần Văn Minh and Phạm Xuân Chiểu.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] A notable omission was the II Corps commander, General Khánh, who was transferred to I Corps, the northernmost Corps and the farthest away from Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1963-south-vietnamese-coup-p02] The Americans recognized the new government on 8 November.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In December 1974, People's Army of Vietnam's (PAVN) forces crossed from their bases in Cambodia and captured Phước Long Province by January 1975.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] After this success, the North Vietnamese leadership increased the scope of the PAVN offensive and attacked the Central Highlands from Cambodia in March, capturing the city of Buôn Ma Thuột on 18 March.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] These operations were intended to be preparatory to launching a general offensive in 1976.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Following these defeats, the South Vietnamese leadership realized they were no longer able to defend the entire country and ordered a strategic withdrawal from the Central Highlands.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The retreat was a disaster as civilian refugees fled under fire alongside soldiers along a single highway to the coast.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] This situation was worsened by confusing orders, lack of command, and a well-led and aggressive enemy, which led to the destruction of most South Vietnamese forces in the Central Highlands.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] A similar collapse occurred in the northern provinces where PAVN forces captured both Huế and Đà Nẵng by the end of March.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Following the ARVN collapse, North Vietnam transferred its northern forces over 350 miles (560 km) south down the Ho Chi Minh trail through Laos and Cambodia to capture the South Vietnamese capital of Saigon and win the war in time to celebrate their late President Ho Chi Minh's birthday.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] South Vietnamese forces regrouped around the capital and defended the key transportation hubs at Phan Rang and Xuân Lộc, but the South Vietnamese had lost the political and military will to continue.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On 21 April, South Vietnamese President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu resigned, hoping the North Vietnamese would reopen negotiations.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] While IV Corps southwest of Saigon remained relatively stable, preventing VC units from capturing any provincial capitals, PAVN forces entered Saigon, forcing the South Vietnamese government, now under the leadership of Dương Văn Minh, to surrender on 30 April 1975.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The signing of the Paris Peace Accords in January 1973 did not end the fighting in South Vietnam since both sides violated the cease-fire and attempted to gain control of as much territory as possible.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Occupation meant population control in any future negotiations or reunification effort.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The fighting that erupted was not small in scale.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The three-phase North Vietnamese "Land-grabbing-and population nibbling" campaign, for example, included four division-sized attacks to seize strategically advantageous positions.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The International Commission of Control and Supervision (ICCS), established by a protocol of the Paris agreement, had been assigned the task of monitoring the implementation of the cease-fire.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The principles of consultation and unanimity among the members, however, doomed any effort to control the situation or to stop cease-fire violations, and the ICCS ceased to function in any meaningful way within a few months of its establishment.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] At the end of 1973, there was serious debate among the Hanoi leadership over future military policy as the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam convened to assess the progress of its efforts in the south.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] General Văn Tiến Dũng, PAVN chief of staff, and Defence Minister Võ Nguyên Giáp strongly urged the resumption of conventional military operations, warning that increasing passivity would affect the morale of the army.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Premier Phạm Văn Đồng, however, feared resuming operations would drain vital resources needed for reconstruction in the north.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The final result of this debate was *Resolution 21*, which called for "strategic raids" on South Vietnamese forces in order to regain territory lost to the ARVN since the conclusion of the Peace Accords and to test the reaction of both the South Vietnamese military and the American government.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The first blows of the new policy were delivered between March and November 1974, when the communists attacked ARVN forces in Quảng Đức Province and at Biên Hòa.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Hanoi's leaders watched closely and anxiously as strikes by American B-52 Stratofortress bombers failed to materialize.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During these operations, however, PAVN retook the military initiative, gaining experience in combined arms operations, depleting ARVN forces, causing them to expend large quantities of ammunition, and gaining avenues of approach and jump-off points for any new offensive.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Thiệu still believed the promise made by President Richard Nixon to reintroduce American air power to the conflict if any serious violations of the agreement took place.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] It was also assumed that U.S. financial and military aid would continue to be forthcoming at previous levels.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Congress passed the Case–Church Amendment, legislation that all but prohibited any direct or indirect U.S. combat activities over or in Laos, Cambodia, and both Vietnams.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On 7 November the legislative branch overrode Nixon's veto of the War Powers Act.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During 1972–1973, South Vietnam had received $2.2 billion in U.S. assistance.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In 1973–1974, that figure was slashed to $965 million, a more than 50 percent reduction.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Nixon's growing political difficulties (especially the Watergate scandal) and the increasing antagonism between the legislative and executive branches over Vietnam policies, did little to dampen South Vietnamese expectations.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Some among the Saigon leadership were more realistic in their appraisal.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] According to Republic of Vietnam Air Force (RVNAF) General Dong Van Khuyen: "Our leaders continued to believe in U.S. air intervention even after the U.S.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] They deluded themselves." The shock of reduced aid was compounded on 9 August, when Richard Nixon, the guarantor of South Vietnamese independence, was forced to resign from office.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In October 1973, the Arab oil embargo began, and the resulting oil shock of 1973–74 caused a massive bout of inflation that largely destroyed the South Vietnamese economy with a spokesman for Thiệu admitting in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] One consequence of the inflation was the South Vietnamese government had increasing difficulty in paying its soldiers.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In April, Thiệu launched the Svay Rieng Campaign against PAVN strongholds in eastern Cambodia.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] This proved to be the last major offensive operation launched by the ARVN.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] While these operations succeeded, the cost in terms of manpower and resources was high.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] By the end of the year the military experienced shortages as a result of decreased American aid, while communist forces continued gaining strength.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] By the end of October the North Vietnamese Politburo decided on its strategy for 1975 and 1976.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In what became known as *Resolution of 1975*, the party leadership reported that the war reached its "final stage".
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The army was to consolidate its gains, eliminate South Vietnamese border outposts and secure its logistical corridor, and continue its force build-up in the south.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During 1976 the final general offensive would begin.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The strategy was undoubtedly conservative, but the North Vietnamese General Staff overestimated the capabilities of the ARVN, which fought well in the summer and into the fall.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] They continually believed that the South Vietnamese, technically at least, were still superior in overall strength.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The following month, PAVN field commanders and their political officers were called to Hanoi to assess the new strategy.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] It was first decided that an attack in the Central Highlands would have the greatest chance of success, but this concept was challenged by Lieutenant General Trần Văn Trà, COSVN's military commander.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] His staff already drew a plan for a direct attack against Saigon, and Trà quickly proposed that his forces launch a probing attack in Phước Long Province to see how well the ARVN would fight and if the U.S. would react.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Trà's plan offered the potential for great gain at low risk.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] After the signing of the Paris Accords, the South Vietnamese government fielded the fourth largest military force in the world as a result of the American Enhance and Enhance Plus programs.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The nation received new combat and transport aircraft, armored vehicles, helicopters, artillery pieces, and other equipment worth $753 million.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The arms shipments were welcomed by Saigon, but the lack of sufficient training and dependence on the U.S. for spare parts, fuel, and ammunition caused maintenance and logistical problems.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] South Vietnamese forces certainly outnumbered combined PAVN/Viet Cong (VC) forces in the south with approximately one and one-half million troops in uniform.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] But almost 482,000 of this number belonged to either the Regional or Popular Forces, organizations of mixed reliability.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Only about 200,000 of the remaining total served as regulars in the combat arms.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The rest were in the administrative and logistical "tail" required to support them (of course, a large proportion of the active PAVN and VC forces were likewise engaged, on the Ho Chi Minh Trail, anti-aircraft networks, administration, etc., as is true of any modern army).
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The ARVN always had problems keeping men in the ranks, but during 1973–75, the problem reached epidemic proportions.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During 1974, for example, only 65 percent of authorized manpower was present for duty at any time.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The nation's officer corps still suffered from the promotion and retention of generals due to their political loyalties, not their professional abilities.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Corruption and incompetence among officers was endemic, with some "raising it almost to an art form." To mollify his critics, President Thiệu sacked the II and IV Corps commanders, Generals Nguyễn Văn Toàn and Nguyễn Vĩnh Nghi, both Thiệu loyalists notorious for corruption.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Unfortunately, both men were also proven leaders, popular with their troops, and versatile on the battlefield.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In 1972, general Creighton Abrams fumed at ARVN complaints that they lacked arms and equipment.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] He said: *“The ARVN haven’t lost their tanks because the enemy tanks knocked them out.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The ARVN lost their tanks because goddamn it, they abandoned them.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] And, shit, if they had the Josef Stalin 3 [tank], it wouldn’t have been any better.”* He likewise harangued President Thieu and Saigon’s chief of staff Cao Van Vien: *“Equipment is not what you need.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] You’ve got all the equipment you need...
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Severe cutbacks in U.S. aid directly affected military performance.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Artillery batteries previously allocated 100 rounds per day were reduced to firing only four daily.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Each ARVN soldier was restricted to only 85 bullets per month.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Because of fuel shortages and a lack of spare parts, sorties by South Vietnamese helicopter and cargo aircraft shrank by 50 to 70 percent.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Due to President Thiệu's "no surrender of territory" command, the army was stretched to the limit defending terrain along a 600-mile frontier.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Even the nation's strategic reserve, the Airborne and Marine Divisions, were occupied in static defensive roles.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The ARVN, schooled by the Americans in rapid mobility and application of massive firepower, were losing the ability to deliver either.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The military situation was exacerbated by the collapse of the South Vietnamese economy and a massive influx of refugees into the cities.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During the same period, the North Vietnamese were recovering from losses incurred during the Easter Offensive of 1972 by replacing personnel and modernizing their equipment with a new influx of Soviet and Chinese military aid.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During 1973, North Vietnam received 2.8 million metric tons of goods (worth $330 million) from communist-bloc countries, a 50 percent increase over the previous year.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In 1974 that total increased to 3.5 million metric tons ($400 million) (according to CIA), while the South's aid was slashed to only $965 million per year, down from $2.2 billion.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] As a result, while South Vietnam suffered a multitude of issues with replacing losses and/or bolstering their military strength, North Vietnam had little trouble doing both.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] By the end of 1974, the North Vietnamese General Staff had created two army corps headquarters, matching South Vietnam's command and control structure in the I and II Corps Tactical Zones.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Most independent PAVN infantry regiments in the south were also combined into divisional structures.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The PAVN high command also recognized the need for improvements to their logistical network to facilitate the transport of sufficient supplies of food, weapons, and ammunition necessary for continuous large-scale operations.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] By 1973 the 559th Transportation Group, which controlled the Ho Chi Minh Trail in southeastern Laos, was ordered to expand east of the Trường Sơn Mountains and directly into South Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The new logistical route, Corridor 613, ran inside South Vietnam from the DMZ to all the way to Lộc Ninh.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Besides creating the new extension, the 559th upgraded its entire network, constructing all-weather, hard-surfaced roads to accommodate the modern mechanized army that had been rebuilt since the Paris Accords.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The work required two years to complete, but the time required for the transport of personnel from North Vietnam to the southernmost seat of battle was reduced from four months to three weeks.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Such systems posed a major deterrent to the RVNAF, since its aircraft were not equipped to deal with such threats.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] As a result, RVNAF aerial interdiction of the communist logistical build-up became almost impossible and reconnaissance flights were held to a minimum.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Ironically, the U.S. decision to provide the RVNAF with unsophisticated aircraft was motivated, in part, by the fear that better aircraft would tempt the South Vietnamese to initiate operations over North Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The less capable aircraft would keep the fighting at a relatively lower level, enhancing the possibility of negotiations.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] This lack of active intelligence collection made estimation of North Vietnamese strength and intentions much more difficult.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] However, deficiencies of the PAVN's armored and heavy artillery forces, essential for attacks on heavily fortified ARVN regimental and divisional base camps, weighed heavily on the minds of the General Staff planners who drew up the plan presented to the Politburo in October 1974.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Much attention was focused on the role ARVN's ammunition shortages played in the collapse of South Vietnam, but it is not known if the PAVN suffered similar shortages.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Soviet and Chinese military aid, especially in the category of "offensive weapon" (armor and artillery), declined significantly since the Paris Accords.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Also, much of PAVN's armor and artillery was in poor condition, and spare parts were in short supply.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Most PAVN artillery units, especially in the South, were still equipped only with light mortar, recoilless gun, or single-tube rocket launchers.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Since China cut down military support it forced the PAVN to use obsolete T-34 tanks and SU-100 tank destroyers in the offensive.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Both ARVN and PAVN tanks and heavy artillery (field artillery and mortars 85mm or larger in caliber) suffered severe ammunition shortages.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] PAVN General Văn Tiến Dũng wrote that, compared to 1973, the 1974 ARVN's "firepower had decreased by nearly 60 percent because of bomb and ammunition shortages.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Its mobility was also reduced by half due to lack of aircraft, vehicles, and fuel...
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The reduction of U.S. aid made it impossible for the puppet troops to carry out their combat plans and build up their forces." Reduction in firepower continued throughout the next year as the ARVN attempted to conserve ammunition.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In the heavy fighting of July 1974 through March 1975, the ARVN expended an average of 18,267 tons of ammunition per month, compared to 66,500 tons per month in 1972, a more than 72% reduction.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On the other side, PAVN's entire stock of heavy artillery and tank ammunition in 1974, including all ammunition held by combat units at forward warehouses, and in the PAVN's strategic reserves, totaled just 100,000 rounds.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The ammunition problem was so serious that the PAVN artillery command had to replace the larger weapons in a number of units with obsolete 76.2 mm and 57 mm artillery pieces drawn out of storage for which there still was adequate ammunition.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Consequently, the offensive would rely partly on captured ARVN stocks.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Many historians maintain that given the massive reductions in US military aid to South Vietnam after 1973, any major PAVN offensive was bound to succeed.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] However, the ARVN's soldiers were hardened veterans, and South Vietnam maintained vast stockpiles of ammunition and equipment (as demonstrated by the massive quantities of war materiel captured by the PAVN when the war ended).
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The final collapse of the ARVN may well have been inevitable, but the end would have been much bloodier and much longer in coming had the PAVN chosen a more direct, conventional plan of attack.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In fact, the most damaging blow of the entire PAVN campaign may have been the crushing psychological blow their skillful and unexpected strategy dealt to the mind of the ARVN's commander-in-chief.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Phước Long was the northernmost provincial capital in III Corps, approximately 75 miles (121 km) northeast of Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] At the end of December 1974, the North Vietnamese 7th and 3rd Divisions, an independent infantry regiment, and armored, anti-aircraft, and heavy artillery support moved out of Cambodia to attack.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The province was defended by five Regional Force battalions, 48 Popular Force platoons and four territorial artillery sections.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] From his headquarters at Biên Hòa, Lieutenant General Dư Quốc Đống, the III Corps commander, augmented this force by sending in the 2nd Battalion, 7th Infantry Regiment of the 5th Division, two artillery sections, and three reconnaissance companies.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The battle for the province began on 13 December when PAVN forces began to isolate Phước Long City's overland communications and eliminating static outposts.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] They then began to bombard Phước Long accurately with heavy artillery and launched a concerted armor/infantry ground attack on the 27th.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Any counterattack or relief effort contemplated by the South Vietnamese was doomed by the thousands of refugees that took to the roads in order to escape the fighting.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Desertion among ARVN units became common, as soldiers began disappearing from the ranks in search of family members.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] This pattern was to become too common as the offensive continued, not just among the territorial forces, but among the regular troops.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On 2 January an emergency meeting was held at the Independence Palace in Saigon between President Thiệu, the Joint General Staff, and General Đống.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] At the meeting, Đống presented a plan for the relief of Phước Long that would have utilized either an infantry division or the Airborne Division.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Phước Long City and province would be surrendered to PAVN forces as a matter of expediency, since it was considered to be strategically less important than Tây Ninh, Pleiku, or Huế – economically, politically, and demographically.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The fighting around Phước Long continued until 6 January 1975, after which the town became the first provincial capital permanently seized by PAVN.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Of the more than 5,400 ARVN troops originally committed to the battle, only 850 returned to government lines.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The PAVN captured 10,000 rounds of artillery ammunition.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] More important for the North Vietnamese was the apparent total indifference with which the U.S. regarded this loss.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The psychological blow for the government and people of South Vietnam was severe.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] According to the chief of the ARVN General Staff, General Cao Văn Viên, *"Almost gone was the hope that the United States would forcibly punish the North Vietnamese for their brazen violations of the cease-fire agreement ...
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Word of the fall of Phước Long reached the North Vietnamese Politburo in the midst of its Twenty-third Plenum, and the body immediately ordered the General Staff to develop a follow-up plan.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The Politburo's assessment that the United States would not re-intervene in the war was proven correct, the weakness of the ARVN's defenses had been exposed, and, just as important, a solution to their most critical ammunition shortage – targeting and capturing ARVN artillery stocks – was found.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Lê Duẩn declared that *"Never have we had military and political conditions so perfect or a strategic advantage so great as we have now."* The first target chosen was Duc Lap Camp, a border outpost in II Corp's Darlac Province.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Once again, Trần Văn Trà's influence drove some members to propose a bolder plan: attack Buôn Ma Thuột, the provincial capital.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] This time, Lê Duẩn was reluctant to agree, that is until Lê Đức Thọ threw his weight behind the more radical strategy.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] General Dũng was ordered south to take direct command of the new offensive, which had been named *Operation 275*.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] General Dũng already worked out a plan for taking Buôn Ma Thuột.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The 320th Division was then to neutralize outposts to the north and seize the Phuong Duc Airfield.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The mission of the 10th Division was to then conduct the main attack on the city along Route 14.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Commanding his forces from Pleiku, Major General Phạm Văn Phú, the III Corps commander, was given adequate warnings of the impending North Vietnamese attacks, but they were not given serious consideration.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Phú was deceived by an elaborate North Vietnamese communications charade and his belief that PAVN movements toward Buôn Ma Thuột were diversionary operations designed to distract him from the true objective, Pleiku.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The defense of Buôn Ma Thuột, therefore, was entrusted to a single Ranger group and Popular and Regional Force units (approximately 4,000 men).
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] They were augmented at the beginning of March by 53rd Regiment of the 23rd Division.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The battle for Buôn Ma Thuột began on 10 March 1975.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Preceded by an intense artillery bombardment, the 10th Division quickly pushed into the city and seized the ammunition depot.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] That evening the 316th Division entered the battle for the city center.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On the 13th, the ARVN 44th Regiment, 23rd Division and a battalion of the 21st Ranger Group were helilifted to Phuoc An, 20 miles (32 km) east of Buôn Ma Thuột, to form a relief force for the beleaguered city.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The column, advancing into the path of thousands of refugees and military dependents fleeing the highlands, soon encountered the 10th Division.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The South Vietnamese attack disintegrated and the force then retreated, joining the civilian exodus.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On 18 March the PAVN had taken Phuoc An, eliminating any hope of reaching Buôn Ma Thuột.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Darlac Province in its entirety then fell under North Vietnamese control.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] ARVN forces began to rapidly shift positions in an attempt to keep the PAVN from quickly pushing eastward to the coastal lowlands.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In the final analysis, the blame for the fall of the highlands lies with General Phú, who refused to act on sound intelligence and when he realized his error, it was too late to get reinforcements to the scene.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Realising the weakened state of his army, President Thiệu sent a delegation to Washington in early March to request an increase in economic and military aid.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Ambassador to South Vietnam Graham Martin, who believed additional aid would help the defense of the Republic, also made a trip to Washington to present the case to President Gerald R.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Congress, increasingly reluctant to divert money from economic recovery into what was seen as a lost cause, slashed a proposed $1.45 billion military aid package for 1975 to $700 million.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] President Thiệu felt increased pressure.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] By 11 March, the day after Buôn Ma Thuột was attacked, Thiệu came to the conclusion there was no longer any hope of receiving a $300 million supplemental aid package he requested from the U.S. government.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On that basis he called a meeting attended by Lieutenant General Đặng Văn Quang and General Viên.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Thiệu then sketched in on the map the areas which he considered most important – all of the III and IV Corps Tactical Zones.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] He also pointed out the areas currently under PAVN/VC control which would have to be retaken.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The key to the location of these operations were concentrations of natural resources – rice, rubber, industry, etc.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Those areas that were to be held also included coastal areas where oil had been discovered on the continental shelf.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Thiệu declared this new strategy as "Light at the top, heavy on the bottom." Viên informed Thiệu that he believed the redeployment was a necessary step, but refrained from mentioning he believed it was too late.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Viên considered that a redeployment on such a scale should have been carried out by mid-1974 or, at the latest, as soon as President Nixon resigned from office.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The critical decision for the Saigon government was made two days later at Cam Ranh Bay during a meeting between Thiệu and General Phu.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Thiệu decided that Pleiku and Kon Tum were to be abandoned and that the forces defending them would be redeployed to retake demographically more important Ban Mê Thuột.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Phu informed the president that the only route possible for the redeployment, given PAVN blocking actions, was little-used Interprovincial Route 7B, a neglected, narrow, rough-surfaced track (actually a logging road) with several downed bridges along its course.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Meanwhile, General Dũng advised Hanoi that he was turning his forces to capture Kon Tum and Pleiku.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In Hanoi, Lê Duẩn was pressuring the General Staff to take advantage of the foothold they gained in the highlands.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Two months remained before the monsoon season, when military operations would be forestalled.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Further strategic gains appeared possible in light of Saigon's apparent weakness and the level of the U.S. response.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] General Phu then faced the monumental task of moving a corps-sized column of troops, equipment, and vehicles over a largely unknown road some 160 miles (260 km) through the mountains and jungles of the highlands to Nha Trang for the attempted counterattack.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The force would consist of one battalion of the 44th ARVN Regiment, five Ranger groups, the 21st Tank Squadron, two 155 mm artillery battalions, one 175 mm battalion and Popular and Regional Force units.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Also in train would be the men and equipment of the 20th Combat Engineer Group and the 231st Direct Support Group.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Phu's excessive preoccupation with secrecy, however, doomed the effort from the beginning.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Operational planning was limited only to a few trusted subordinates who had either contributed to or knew about it.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The chief of staff of II Corps, for example, admitted that he was completely in the dark about the planned abandonment of Pleiku and Kon Tum.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Command of the convoy itself was handed over to the commander of the II Corps Rangers.Phu further muddied the command arrangements by appointing his assistant for operations to also oversee the withdrawal.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During the first two days of the move (16 and 17 March) the effort went well, until, at Hau Bon, the column of refugees from the abandoned cities and the military convoys collided and became stuck.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Making matters worse was that combat engineers had to complete a pontoon bridge across the Đà Rằng River.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The 968th Division was ordered to force its way through Pleiku and strike the tail of the retreat.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The following day the column only proceeded 15 miles (24 km) before it encountered a significant PAVN roadblock.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] From that point onward the exodus kept moving forward only by fighting its way ahead.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] "They hit us with everything" said Ranger Private Nguyen Van Sau, describing an unrelenting shower of artillery shells, mortar rounds and rockets that flew from the jungle into the stream of refugees.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Upon reaching the Đà Rằng River, only 20 kilometers from Tuy Hòa, a pontoon bridge had to be helilifted to the column.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] By 22 March the bridge was completed, but the advance became more hazardous due to numerous PAVN units moving into blocking positions.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During the entire movement, the RVNAF provided minimal support due to bad weather.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On 27 March the final roadblock was overcome and, at 21:00, the first vehicles of the column entered Tuy Hòa.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] "How many people in the original column survived the tragic journey, no one knew exactly." It was estimated by the ARVN that only 20,000 of the 60,000 troops that had started out from Pleiku finally reached the coast.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Of the estimated 180,000 civilians that fled the highlands with the column, only about 60,000 got through.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Those who failed to break through were either killed or taken prisoner by PAVN forces.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The retreat from the Central Highlands became a rout of strategic proportions.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Buoyed by their easy triumph, the PAVN 10th, 316th and 320th Divisions began to move toward the coast.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The only thing stand before them was the ARVN 22nd Division, tasked with defending the mountain passes to the coast.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] However, by late March, these PAVN units would make it into Huế and Da Nang.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On 30 March the 22nd Division was ordered to proceed to the coast at Qui Nhơn for evacuation.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] North Vietnamese forces attacked them there from the north and two of the division's regiments had to fight their way through to the beaches for pick-up.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] At 02:00 on 1 April, what was left of the division was extracted by sea.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Two regimental colonels, after being ordered to evacuate, refused to leave, preferring suicide rather than retreat or surrender.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The division's third regiment, the 47th, ran into an ambush at Phu Cat and suffered heavy casualties, losing about half of its troops.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] When it later regrouped at Vũng Tàu, the 22nd numbered only slightly over 2,000 men, its commander also having chosen suicide over surrender.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The situation for the South Vietnamese in the I Corps Tactical Zone regained some stability after the defeat of a three-division PAVN push during late 1974.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] By early the following year, I Corps fielded three infantry divisions (the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd), the elite Airborne and Marine Divisions, four Ranger Groups and the 1st Armored Brigade.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The northern provinces were under the command of one of South Vietnam's finest and most aggressive generals, Ngô Quang Trưởng.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Until mid-March, the PAVN had limited their offensive operations to attempts to cut Highway 1, the main north–south line of communication, between Huế and Da Nang and between Da Nang and Chu Lai.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] To confront the South Vietnamese, PAVN Brigadier General Lê Trọng Tấn had amassed a force of five divisions and nine independent infantry regiments, three sapper regiments, three armored regiments, twelve anti-aircraft and eight artillery regiments.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] At a meeting in Saigon on 13 March President Thiệu was briefed on the military situation by Trưởng and the new III Corps commander, Lieutenant General Nguyễn Văn Toàn.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Thiệu then laid out his plan for national consolidation.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] As Trưởng understood it, he was free to redeploy his forces to hold the Da Nang area.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] This South Vietnam's second largest city was to be held due to possible future exploitation of offshore oil deposits.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Trưởng was shocked to discover, however, that the Airborne Division was to be removed to III Corps.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] (Unknown to Trưởng at the time, the Marine Division was also already slated for redeployment with both units then forming a new national reserve).
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] General Trưởng was recalled to Saigon on 19 March to brief Thiệu on his withdrawal plan.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] This was to be only an interim measure, however, since the forces that withdrew to Huế and Chu Lai would then be sea-lifted to Da Nang by the Republic of Vietnam Navy.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The president then stunned the general by announcing he misinterpreted his previous orders: Huế was not to be abandoned.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Making matters worse, Trưởng discovered that his force was to be reduced by the removal of the Marine Division.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] By the time of the second meeting it was obvious that the second plan was the only possible recourse, since any phased withdrawal along Highway 1 had become impossible.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] This was due to increasing PAVN pressure that the ARVN was barely containing and the enormous and uncontrolled flow of refugees along the highway.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Trưởng then requested permission for a withdrawal of his forces into the three enclaves as planned and for the retention of the Marines.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Trưởng returned to Da Nang the same day and was greeted by bad news.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The PAVN had begun an all-out offensive in I Corps and already breached Trưởng's northern defense line at the Thạch Hãn River.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] President Thiệu made a nationwide radio broadcast that afternoon proclaiming that Huế would be held "at all costs." That evening Trưởng ordered a retreat to a new defense line at the My Chanh River, thereby ceding all of Quảng Trị Province to the PAVN.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Meanwhile, the PAVN offensive was slowly rolling over ARVN opposition north and south of Da Nang.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] General Dong's plan called for attacks on the area from the west, north, and south that would drive South Vietnamese forces into Da Nang, where they could be destroyed.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The highway between Huế and Da Nang was cut at Phú Lộc after severe fighting on 22 March.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] South of Da Nang, the ARVN 2nd Division barely managed to contain a PAVN drive toward Tam Kỳ and the coastal plain.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On the morning of 24 March, however, the 711th Division, backed by armored elements, seized Tam Kỳ, driving the population north toward Da Nang by the thousands.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] PAVN forces then cut Highway 1 between Quảng Ngãi and Chu Lai, a move to which the 2nd Division was too battered to respond.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] With Corps approval, South Vietnamese troops from Quảng Ngãi fought their way northward, but only a few managed to reach Chu Lai.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In a single day the situation in I Corps had deteriorated beyond control.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] This effort was undertaken in order for Trưởng to obey a Joint General Staff directive that he conduct the defense of Da Nang without the Marines, who were to be withdrawn to the south.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] The same lack of planning and hasty withdrawal along unprotected routes to meet the evacuation deadline cost the 2nd Division two-thirds of its men and most of its equipment.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Only 7,000 troops and around 3,000 civilians were evacuated from Chu Lai.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During 26 March, command and control collapsed and discipline in the 1st Division eroded after its commander told his men "We've been betrayed ...
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] It is now *sauve qui peut* (every man for himself) ...
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] See you in Da Nang." The overland march, pummelled by artillery the entire way, degenerated into chaos as it moved toward Da Nang.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] No sooner had the remains of the force reached the city than soldiers began to melt away, searching for their dependents.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] On the coast near Huế, only one regiment of the 1st Division, about 600 marines and 7,700 civilians were picked up by naval vessels.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] With escape impossible, five battalion commanders of the Marine Division said their farewells and then shot themselves rather than face capture.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] From the north, two PAVN divisions, along with armor and artillery elements, enveloped the western flank of Da Nang.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] To the south, two more divisions closed in and brought the center of the city into artillery range.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Da Nang then collapsed into anarchy and chaos.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] "Hunger, looting, and crimes were widespread.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] "He did not tell General Trưởng whether to withdraw or to hold and fight" said General Viên, who was with Thiệu.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] When his communications with Saigon were cut, and on his own initiative, Trưởng ordered a naval withdrawal that was to begin the following morning, 29 March.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Thousands of soldiers and civilians rushed for the sea, where hundreds drowned trying to reach the ships that could not dock due to the low tide.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Thousands more died under the continuous PAVN artillery barrage.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Of the ARVN's four infantry divisions, four Ranger groups, armored brigade, air division and thousands of territorial, support, and staff personnel, only around 16,000 were evacuated as the PAVN swept in on 29 March.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Of the almost two million civilians that packed Da Nang at the end of March, a little more than 50,000 were evacuated during the sea lift.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Left behind were 70,000 ARVN troops taken prisoner by northern forces.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] Also abandoned were 33 undamaged RVNAF A-37 jet fighters at Da Nang Air Base and nearly 60 more aircraft at Phu Cat Air Base.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] During the fall of Da Nang no pitched battles had been fought and few of the ARVN troops stationed in and around the city had even raised their rifles in its defense.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p01] In quick succession the few remaining centers of resistance along the coastline "fell like a row of porcelain vases sliding off a shelf": Quảng Ngãi on 24 March; Qui Nhơn and Nha Trang on 1 April; and Cam Ranh Bay on 3 April.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] By 25 March the North Vietnamese Politburo no longer felt it was necessary to wait until 1976 for the initiation of its final offensive against Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] General Dũng was ordered to abandon the long-standing doctrine of meticulous planning and methodical preparation of the battlefield in order that the "puppet regime" could be crushed and the war ended.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The only obstacle to that goal was moving his northern forces 370 miles (600 km) (the reserve divisions in North Vietnam would have to move 1,000 miles (1,600 km)) south in order to participate in the attack on the capital Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] In one of the most complex logistical feats of the war, he proceeded to do just that.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] On 7 April Lê Đức Thọ arrived at Dũng's headquarters near Loc Ninh to oversee the final battles as the Politburo's representative.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] This effort was placed under the command of General Lê Trọng Tấn, the "conqueror of Da Nang." To divert Saigon's attention and prevent the reinforcement of Xuân Lộc, the recently activated 223rd Tactical Group would cut off Route 4, severing Saigon from the Mekong Delta.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Simultaneously, the 3rd Corps would conduct another diversionary operation around Tây Ninh.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] To support the effort, other PAVN elements would close on the city from the west and south.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Since no code name had been applied to the new offensive, Dũng suggested that it be named the *Ho Chi Minh Campaign*.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Lê Đức Thọ then passed on a message from Tôn Đức Thắng, president of North Vietnam to General Dũng: "You must win.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The defense of Xuân Lộc had been entrusted to the 18th Division, reinforced by the 8th Regiment of the 5th Division, the 3rd Armored Brigade, two Ranger and two artillery battalions and the 81st Airborne Ranger Group.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The week-long fighting that erupted on 8 April raged in and around Xuân Lộc and became the most significant engagement of the entire offensive.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The initial attack was conducted by the PAVN 341st and 3rd Divisions, which attacked headlong into the town, a tactic widely used before, hoping to quickly rout the defender.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] However, they had to call off the attack after meeting 2 weeks of heavy resistance and effective fire support which cost them dearly.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The attackers were then reinforced by the 7th Division.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] After the interdiction of an ARVN armored task force sent to the relief of the town along Route 1, the 1st Airborne Brigade was helilifted into the outskirts of the town.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The South Vietnamese committed 25,000 troops to the battle, almost one-third of the remainder of their reserve forces.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] For the first time since the onset of the North Vietnamese offensive, the RVNAF consistently provided effective close air support to the defenders.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] On 14 April General Dũng received new instructions from Hanoi.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] "We must be in Saigon to celebrate Ho Chi Minh's birthday." That deadline, 19 May, was only one month away.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] At that point, Dũng decided to bypass the defenders at Xuân Lộc and commenced the shelling of Biên Hòa Air Base, effectively ending air support.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The PAVN also shifted their original target, instead of charging straight at the town, they instead attacked and destroyed the outposts around Xuân Lộc, cutting off the 18th Division from their reinforcements.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Threatened with encirclement, the 18th Division managed to conduct a retreat to the south along Route 2.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] After more than three weeks of intense fighting, the 18th Division alone suffered 30 percent casualties (around 4000 soldiers) while dealing over 5,000 North Vietnamese casualties and destroying 37 tanks and vehicles.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] However, their defences made no differences to the outcome of the war, as the 18th disintegrated shortly after in the fighting around Biên Hòa.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] With all of Long Khánh Province under PAVN control, General Dũng was free to completely encircle Saigon with his forces.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Even after the loss of Da Nang, "the worst single disaster in the history of South Vietnam", the Ford administration continued to disbelieve that the Saigon regime was failing.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] On 10 April President Ford went to Congress to request a $722 million supplemental military aid package for South Vietnam plus $250 million in economic and refugee aid.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The president's rationale for the aid had changed.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Congress was not impressed, believing that the administration might simply be stalling the evacuation of remaining U.S. personnel and civilians in order to force the aid bill through.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] There would be no more funds for Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The ARVN III Corps commander, General Toan, organized five centers of resistance for the defense of the city.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] These fronts were so connected as to form an arc enveloping the area west, north, and east of the capital.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] South Vietnamese defensive forces around Saigon totaled approximately 60,000 troops.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] On 17 April the Cambodian capital of Phnom Penh fell to the Khmer Rouge, and the US did nothing for their former ally.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] On 21 April 1975, Thiệu, under intense political pressure, resigned as president when his closest domestic allies began losing confidence over his handling of the war.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] In his televised farewell speech, Thiệu admitted, for the first time, having ordered the evacuation of the Central Highlands and the north that led to debacle.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] He then stated that it was the inevitable course of action in the situation – but also insisted it was the generals who failed him.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] He went on to excoriate the U.S., attacking "our great ally...the leader of the free world ...
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The United States has not respected its promises" he declared "It is inhumane.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Immediately following the speech, the presidency was handed over to Vice President Trần Văn Hương.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] At his new forward command post at Ben Cat, General Dũng prepared plans for the final battle.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] He encircled Saigon with four PAVN corps and the hastily assembled 232nd Tactical Force, a total of 19 divisions plus supporting artillery and armored units, approximately 130,000 men.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The attacks on the periphery began on 26 April and the main attack on the city center began the following day.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] After Thiệu's resignation, the South Vietnamese military situation increasingly declined.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] On the 26th, the PAVN launched an all-out attack to take Biên Hòa and the sprawling logistical complex at Long Binh from the south and southeast.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Three days later, the port city of Vũng Tàu was under assault and the pressure against the Cu Chi front was intense.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The same disorganization, loss of control, and anarchy that befell I and II Corps now took place in Saigon, where martial law was imposed to control the chaos and lawlessness.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Although contemplation of a communist victory by that time had created severe shock in many parts of South Vietnamese society, most did little or nothing to forestall it.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] As the main attack developed on April 27th, the South Vietnamese General Assembly handed over the presidency to General Dương Văn Minh, who was sworn in the following day.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] It was widely assumed that Minh, who had no history of aggressive action against the communists, would be able to establish a cease-fire and re-open negotiations.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] However, for the first time since the First Indochina War, the communists held the upper hand on the battlefield and victory was within reach, regardless of any political changes in Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] As a result, they were not willing to agree to a ceasefire, even with Minh at the helm.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The inauguration of Minh served as a signal to South Vietnamese officers who "would make no compromise with the communists", and were responsible for the torture and imprisonment of many VC agents and their sympathizers.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] They began to pack up and try to find a way out of the country.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The aerial evacuation of U.S. personnel and civilians had commenced on 1 April from Tan Son Nhut.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Marine Corps Lance Corporal Darwin Judge and Corporal Charles McMahon, Jr., who were manning a checkpoint at the base's main gate, were killed during a rocket attack.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] They were the last American servicemen killed in Vietnam.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] At 10:51 on 29 April Operation Frequent Wind, the U.S. helicopter evacuation of military and embassy personnel, U.S. civilians, and South Vietnamese citizens thought to be at risk of communist reprisal, was implemented as the city descended into pandemonium.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] By the end of the evacuation, more than 40 ships of the U.S.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Seventh Fleet had collected 1,373 Americans and 5,595 Vietnamese from U.S. helicopters and some 60,000 from boats and aircraft.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Total evacuees included 57,507 removed by air and 73,000 by sea.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] On 28 April PAVN forces fought their way into the outskirts of the city.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] At the Newport Bridge (*Cầu Tân Cảng*), about 3 miles (4.8 km) from the city center, ARVN soldiers battled with PAVN troops attempting to control the span, cutting the city's last overland connection to the south and gaining immediate access to downtown Saigon.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Later that afternoon, as President Minh finished his acceptance speech, a formation of four A-37s, captured from RVNAF, bombed Tan Son Nhut Air Base.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] As Biên Hòa was falling, General Toan fled to Saigon, informing the government that most of the top ARVN leadership resigned themselves to defeat.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Despite the increased disintegration of the ARVN, the PAVN faced heavy resistance, even counterattack attempts to push them out.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The outskirts and downtown of the city become battlefields, where PAVN/VC fought against a rag-tag formation of ARVN soldiers who made their way into Saigon, but couldn't be evacuated.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] These men, betrayed by their commanders, either stripped off their uniforms and hid, or made suicidal assault at the enemy, hoping for a quick death.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Those units tasked with capturing key structures found themselves at the receiving end of a more disciplined force commanded by officers denied their evacuation.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] These men would take advantage of the equipment left over by their escaped comrades and set a perimeter around the city.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] However, despite all efforts, a loose combination of troops either wanting to flee or wanting to kill as many communists as possible before their deaths, mostly leaderless and cut off from supplies, could not hope to stand against a disciplined army with artillery and armored support.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Ambassador Martin boarded a helicopter and departed from the US Embassy, Saigon on one of the last American evacuation flights.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Marines were lifted from the roof of the U.S.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] President Minh ordered all South Vietnamese forces to cease fighting.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Later Minh would be escorted to a radio station, from which he declared the unconditional surrender of his government.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Around noon, a PAVN tank, number 390, crashed through the gates of the Independence Palace.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] A crewman from the 843, which rammed into the side gate and got stuck, jumped out, ran up the steps, carrying the flag of the Provisional Revolutionary Government.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The total number of South Vietnamese evacuated by the U.S. or self-evacuated and ending up in the custody of the United States for processing as refugees to enter the United States totaled 138,869.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] In the Mekong Delta, where South Vietnamese military forces still appeared intact and aggressive, IV Corps deputy commander Brigadier General Lê Văn Hưng planned to build a "secret section", to use the delta's agricultural wealth to form a resistance.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Weeks before the Fall of Saigon, most of the provincial capitals in IV Corps were stable defended by aggressive ARVN military defenses.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] However, VC units began to engage ARVN forces and succeeded in isolating IV Corps from Saigon which put an end to the "secret section" plan.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] When President Minh announced the surrender of South Vietnam, IV Corps started to disintegrate.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Both Lê Văn Hưng and IV Corps commander Nguyễn Khoa Nam disagreed with the surrender order.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] At 8 pm, VC units captured some regional districts in Mekong Delta.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Although Lê Văn Hưng and a number of ARVN soldiers planned to continue to battle against VC units in Can Tho, many residents of Can Tho opposed continued resistance believing the VC would start shelling Can Tho causing numerous casualties in the city.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Lê Văn Hưng agreed to stand down the defense of Can Tho due to the poor options for escape or prolonged defense.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Around 8 P.M, Lê Văn Hưng told his remaining soldiers that he did not want to endure a siege similar to what he had experienced at An Lộc in 1972.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] He later committed suicide and the defense of Can Tho was finished.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] On the same day, Brigadier General Trần Văn Hai committed suicide in Dong Tam Base Camp.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The other ARVN general in the Mekong Delta, Major Nguyễn Khoa Nam, also committed suicide after the surrender, in the early morning of 1 May 1975 at his IV Corps headquarters in Can Tho.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] He did so after hearing of Lê Văn Hưng's suicide.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] By 3 May 1975, North Vietnamese forces controlled all of South Vietnam, just 55 days after opening their attack on Buôn Ma Thuột.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Since the end of the war, there has been much historical recrimination and discussion as to how and why such a lopsided victory had occurred.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Four main lines of thought have remained particularly viable, all of which possess some validity, but all are also open to argument.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The first argument is that the Paris Peace Accords that ended the direct American participation in the war was seriously flawed, because it permitted the North Vietnamese to maintain their forces within territorial South Vietnam after the signing of the agreement, thereby dooming the ceasefire.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The second argument is that the refusal of the United States government to take promised military action in the face of North Vietnamese violations of the ceasefire was key to the defeat.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Adherents to this claim believed that South Vietnam could have been saved by another U.S. bombing campaign.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The conflict between the executive and legislative branches of the American government, already severe before Operation Linebacker II in 1972, was only more exasperating during 1975, when a new campaign would probably only have provoked even more Congressional outrage.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The third cause of the defeat was that the U.S.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Congress simply wrote off and abandoned the Saigon government.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Richard Nixon later stated that the collapse should be laid solely at the door of a "Congress [which] refused to fulfill our obligations [and that this] tragic and irresponsible action" was to blame for losing of the war.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Historian Arnold Isaacs, who was on the scene in South Vietnam at the time, believed that "The psychological damage of the aid cuts was almost certainly greater than the real ...
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Other plausible reasons for the rapidity of the defeat were the American policy of Vietnamization as a prescription for defeat.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The rapid and accelerating withdrawal of U.S. forces that had begun in 1969 caught the South Vietnamese unprepared.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The withdrawals were simply conducted faster than the South Vietnamese could or would improve.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] General Hinh believed that Vietnamization did not "provide the ARVN with enough time ...
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] While the troop increases could be achieved rapidly, it was almost impossible to improve the quality and technical capabilities ...within the span of a few years.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Army general officers who served in Vietnam, conducted by General Douglas Kinnard in 1974, found them agreeing with this assessment.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The South Vietnamese military had greater problems than a reduction in American aid.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] President Thiệu was a disaster as commander-in-chief.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] During the two years before the offensive (when aid cuts were already occurring), neither he nor the General Staff made adjustments in strategy, doctrine, organization, or training to compensate for the inevitability of further aid reductions.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Thiệu also deprived local commanders of any strategic or tactical flexibility in decision-making, which flowed downward from the presidential palace and those decisions contributed to the defeat.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Added to these problems were the long-standing corruption and incompetence within the officer corps.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Early defeats during the final campaign were compounded not by a lack of will or ability on the part of the enlisted men, but by the cowardice and failing morale of the officers.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] According to Isaacs, "The army did not collapse in its foxholes or for lack of supplies.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Key to the defeat of South Vietnam was the ability of the officers and men of the PAVN.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] The highly motivated and newly modernized PAVN was, for the first time, freed from the restraints of previous combat doctrine.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] What began as a conservative strategy, devised in Hanoi, was outrun by its local successes.
[src:vietnam/1975-spring-offensive-p02] Battlefield commanders were then given a new flexibility, which increased the tempo of operations and allowed them to quickly apply concentrated power at strategic points.
